# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clifford-algebra
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In mathematics, a **bivector** or **2-vector** is a quantity in exterior algebra or geometric algebra that extends the idea of scalars and vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Considering a scalar as a degree-zero quantity and a vector as a degree-one quantity, a bivector is of degree two.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Bivectors have applications in many areas of mathematics and physics.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] They are related to complex numbers in two dimensions and to both pseudovectors and vector quaternions in three dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] They can be used to generate rotations in a space of any number of dimensions, and are a useful tool for classifying such rotations.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Geometrically, a simple bivector can be interpreted as characterizing a **directed plane segment** (or **oriented plane segment**), much as vectors can be thought of as characterizing *directed line segments*.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In layman terms, any surface defines the same bivector if it is parallel to the same plane (same attitude), has the same area, and same orientation (see figure).
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Bivectors are generated by the exterior product on vectors: given two vectors **a** and **b**, their exterior product **a** ∧ **b** is a bivector, as is any sum of bivectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Not all bivectors can be expressed as an exterior product without such summation.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] More precisely, a bivector that can be expressed as an exterior product is called *simple*; in up to three dimensions all bivectors are simple, but in higher dimensions this is not the case.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The exterior product of two vectors is alternating, so **a** ∧ **a** is the zero bivector, and **b** ∧ **a** = −**a** ∧ **b**, producing the opposite orientation.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Concepts directly related to bivectors are rank-2 antisymmetric tensor and skew-symmetric matrix.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The bivector was first defined in 1844 by German mathematician Hermann Grassmann in exterior algebra as the result of the exterior product of two vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Just the previous year, in Ireland, William Rowan Hamilton had discovered quaternions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Hamilton coined both *vector* and *bivector*, the latter in his *Lectures on Quaternions* (1853) as he introduced biquaternions, which have bivectors for their vector parts.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] It was not until English mathematician William Kingdon Clifford in 1888 added the geometric product to Grassmann's algebra, incorporating the ideas of both Hamilton and Grassmann, and founded Clifford algebra, that the bivector of this article arose.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Henry Forder used the term *bivector* to develop exterior algebra in 1941.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In the 1890s Josiah Willard Gibbs and Oliver Heaviside developed vector calculus, which included separate cross product and dot products that were derived from quaternion multiplication.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The success of vector calculus, and of the book *Vector Analysis* by Gibbs and Wilson, had the effect that the insights of Hamilton and Clifford were overlooked for a long time, since much of 20th century mathematics and physics was formulated in vector terms.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Gibbs used vectors to fill the role of bivectors in three dimensions, and used bivector in Hamilton's sense, a use that has sometimes been copied.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Today the bivector is largely studied as a topic in geometric algebra, a Clifford algebra over real or complex vector spaces with a quadratic form.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Its resurgence was led by David Hestenes who, along with others, applied geometric algebra to a range of new applications in physics.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] For this article, the bivector will be considered only in real geometric algebras, which may be applied in most areas of physics.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Also unless otherwise stated, all examples have a Euclidean metric and so a positive-definite quadratic form.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The bivector arises from the definition of the geometric product over a vector space with an associated quadratic form sometimes called the *metric*.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] When **b** is not parallel to and hence not a scalar multiple of **a**, **ab** cannot be a scalar.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] From the law of cosines on the triangle formed by the vectors its value is |**a**| |**b**| cos *θ*, where θ is the angle between the vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] It is symmetric, scalar-valued, and can be used to determine the angle between two vectors: in particular if **a** and **b** are orthogonal the product is zero.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] That is, the geometric product is the sum of the symmetric scalar product and alternating exterior product.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] With a negative square, it cannot be a scalar or vector quantity, so it is a new sort of object, a **bivector**.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] It has magnitude |**a**| |**b**| |sin *θ*|, where *θ* is the angle between the vectors, and so is zero for parallel vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] although other conventions are used, in particular as vectors and bivectors are both elements of the geometric algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The algebra generated by the geometric product (that is, all objects formed by taking repeated sums and geometric products of scalars and vectors) is the geometric algebra over the vector space.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] For an Euclidean vector space, this algebra is written ${\mathcal {G}}_{n}$ or Cl*n*(**R**), where n is the dimension of the vector space **R***n*.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Cl*n*(**R**) is both a vector space and an algebra, generated by all the products between vectors in **R***n*, so it contains all vectors and bivectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] More precisely, as a vector space it contains the vectors and bivectors as linear subspaces, though not as subalgebras (since the geometric product of two vectors is not generally another vector).
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The space of all bivectors has dimension ⁠1/2⁠*n*(*n* − 1) and is written ⋀2**R***n*, and is the second exterior power of the original vector space.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The subalgebra generated by the bivectors is the *even subalgebra* of the geometric algebra, written Cl[0] *n*(**R**).
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This algebra results from considering all repeated sums and geometric products of scalars and bivectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] It has dimension 2*n*−1, and contains ⋀2**R***n* as a linear subspace.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In two and three dimensions the even subalgebra contains only scalars and bivectors, and each is of particular interest.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In two dimensions, the even subalgebra is isomorphic to the complex numbers, **C**, while in three it is isomorphic to the quaternions, **H**.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The even subalgebra contains the rotations in any dimension.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] As noted in the previous section the magnitude of a simple bivector, that is one that is the exterior product of two vectors **a** and **b**, is |**a**| |**b**| sin *θ*, where θ is the angle between the vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] It is written |**B**|, where **B** is the bivector.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] For general bivectors, the magnitude can be calculated by taking the norm of the bivector considered as a vector in the space ⋀2**R***n*.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] If the magnitude is zero then all the bivector's components are zero, and the bivector is the zero bivector which as an element of the geometric algebra equals the scalar zero.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] A unit bivector is one with unit magnitude.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Of particular utility are the unit bivectors formed from the products of the standard basis of the vector space.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] If **e***i* and **e***j* are distinct basis vectors then the product **e***i* ∧ **e***j* is a bivector.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The set of all bivectors produced from the basis in this way form a basis for ⋀2**R***n*.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The exterior product of two vectors is a bivector, but not all bivectors are exterior products of two vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] cannot be written as the exterior product of two vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] A bivector that can be written as the exterior product of two vectors is simple.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In two and three dimensions all bivectors are simple, but not in four or more dimensions; in four dimensions every bivector is the sum of at most two exterior products.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] A bivector has a real square if and only if it is simple, and only simple bivectors can be represented geometrically by a directed plane area.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The quantity **A** · **B** is the scalar-valued scalar product, while **A** ∧ **B** is the grade 4 exterior product that arises in four or more dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The space of bivectors ⋀2**R***n* is a Lie algebra over **R**, with the commutator product as the Lie bracket.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The full geometric product of bivectors generates the even subalgebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Of particular interest is the product of a bivector with itself.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] If the bivector is *simple* the last term is zero and the product is the scalar-valued **A** · **A**, which can be used as a check for simplicity.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In particular the exterior product of bivectors only exists in four or more dimensions, so all bivectors in two and three dimensions are simple.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Bivectors are isomorphic to skew-symmetric matrices in any number of dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This multiplied by vectors on both sides gives the same vector as the product of a vector and bivector minus the exterior product; an example is the angular velocity tensor.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Skew symmetric matrices generate orthogonal matrices with determinant 1 through the exponential map.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In particular, applying the exponential map to a bivector that is associated with a rotation yields a rotation matrix.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] and the matrix *M**R* can be also calculated directly from rotor R.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Bivectors are related to the eigenvalues of a rotation matrix.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Given a rotation matrix M the eigenvalues can be calculated by solving the characteristic equation for that matrix 0 = det(*M* − *λI*).
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] By the fundamental theorem of algebra this has three roots (only one of which is real as there is only one eigenvector, i.e., the axis of rotation).
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The other roots must be a complex conjugate pair.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] They have unit magnitude so purely imaginary logarithms, equal to the magnitude of the bivector associated with the rotation, which is also the angle of rotation.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The eigenvectors associated with the complex eigenvalues are in the plane of the bivector, so the exterior product of two non-parallel eigenvectors results in the bivector (or a multiple thereof).
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] When working with coordinates in geometric algebra it is usual to write the basis vectors as (**e**1, **e**2, ...), a convention that will be used here.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] A vector in real two-dimensional space **R**2 can be written **a** = *a*1**e**1 + *a*2**e**2, where *a*1 and *a*2 are real numbers, **e**1 and **e**2 are orthonormal basis vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] All bivectors in two dimensions are of this form, that is multiples of the bivector **e**1**e**2, written **e**12 to emphasise it is a bivector rather than a vector.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The term unit bivector can be used in other dimensions but it is only uniquely defined (up to a sign) in two dimensions and all bivectors are multiples of **e**12.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] As the highest grade element of the algebra **e**12 is also the pseudoscalar which is given the symbol i.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] With the properties of negative square and unit magnitude, the unit bivector can be identified with the imaginary unit from complex numbers.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The bivectors and scalars together form the even subalgebra of the geometric algebra, which is isomorphic to the complex numbers **C**.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The complex numbers are usually identified with the coordinate axes and two-dimensional vectors, which would mean associating them with the vector elements of the geometric algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] There is no contradiction in this, as to get from a general vector to a complex number an axis needs to be identified as the real axis, **e**1 say.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This multiplies by all vectors to generate the elements of even subalgebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] All the properties of complex numbers can be derived from bivectors, but two are of particular interest.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] First as with complex numbers products of bivectors and so the even subalgebra are commutative.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This is only true in two dimensions, so properties of the bivector in two dimensions that depend on commutativity do not usually generalise to higher dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Of these the last product is the one that generalises into higher dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In three dimensions all bivectors are simple and so the result of an exterior product.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The unit bivectors **e**23, **e**31 and **e**12 form a basis for the space of bivectors ⋀2**R**3, which is itself a three-dimensional linear space.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The exterior product of two bivectors in three dimensions is zero.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This is another version of Euler's formula, but with a general bivector in three dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Unlike in two dimensions bivectors are not commutative so properties that depend on commutativity do not apply in three dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The element **e**123 is a trivector and the pseudoscalar for the geometry.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Bivectors in three dimensions are sometimes identified with pseudovectors to which they are related, as discussed below.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Bivectors are not closed under the geometric product, but the even subalgebra is.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In three dimensions it consists of all scalar and bivector elements of the geometric algebra, so a general element can be written for example *a* + **A**, where a is the scalar part and **A** is the bivector part.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The even subalgebra, that is the algebra consisting of scalars and bivectors, is isomorphic to the quaternions, **H**.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This can be seen by comparing the basis to the quaternion basis, or from the above product which is identical to the quaternion product, except for a change of sign which relates to the negative products in the bivector scalar product **A** · **B**.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Other quaternion properties can be similarly related to or derived from geometric algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This suggests that the usual split of a quaternion into scalar and vector parts would be better represented as a split into scalar and bivector parts; if this is done the quaternion product is merely the geometric product.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] It also relates quaternions in three dimensions to complex numbers in two, as each is isomorphic to the even subalgebra for the dimension, a relationship that generalises to higher dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The rotation vector, from the axis–angle representation of rotations, is a compact way of representing rotations in three dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In its most compact form, it consists of a vector, the product of a unit vector *ω* that is the axis of rotation with the (signed) angle of rotation *θ*, so that the magnitude of the overall rotation vector *θω* equals the (unsigned) rotation angle.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In geometric algebra the rotation is represented by a bivector.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This can be seen in its relation to quaternions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Let **Ω** be a unit bivector in the plane of rotation, and let θ be the angle of rotation.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The quaternion closely corresponds to the exponential of half of the bivector **Ω***θ*.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The exponential can be defined in terms of its power series, and easily evaluated using the fact that **Ω** squared is −1.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] So rotations can be represented by bivectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Just as quaternions are elements of the geometric algebra, they are related by the exponential map in that algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The bivector **Ω***θ* generates a rotation through the exponential map.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] As in two dimensions, the quantity exp(−⁠1/2⁠**Ω***θ*) is called a rotor and written R.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This is identical to two dimensions, except here rotors are four-dimensional objects isomorphic to the quaternions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This can be generalised to all dimensions, with rotors, elements of the even subalgebra with unit magnitude, being generated by the exponential map from bivectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] They form a double cover over the rotation group, so the rotors R and −*R* represent the same rotation.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The rotation vector is an example of an axial vector.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Axial vectors, or pseudovectors, are vectors with the special feature that their coordinates undergo a sign change relative to the usual vectors (also called "polar vectors") under inversion through the origin, reflection in a plane, or other orientation-reversing linear transformation.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Examples include quantities like torque, angular momentum and vector magnetic fields.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Quantities that would use axial vectors in vector algebra are properly represented by bivectors in geometric algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Note that if the underlying orientation is reversed by inversion through the origin, both the identification of the axial vectors with the usual vectors and the Hodge dual change sign, but the bivectors don't budge.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This is easier to use as the product is just the geometric product.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] But it is antisymmetric because (as in two dimensions) the unit pseudoscalar i squares to −1, so a negative is needed in one of the products.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Bivectors have a number of advantages over axial vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] They better disambiguate axial and polar vectors, that is the quantities represented by them, so it is clearer which operations are allowed and what their results are.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] For example, the inner product of a polar vector and an axial vector resulting from the cross product in the triple product should result in a pseudoscalar, a result which is more obvious if the calculation is framed as the exterior product of a vector and bivector.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] They generalise to other dimensions; in particular bivectors can be used to describe quantities like torque and angular momentum in two as well as three dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Also, they closely match geometric intuition in a number of ways, as seen in the next section.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] As suggested by their name and that of the algebra, bivectors have a natural geometric interpretation.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This appies in any dimension number but is best illustrated in three, where parallels can be drawn with more familiar objects.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In two dimensions the geometric interpretation is trivial, as the space is two-dimensional so has only one plane, and all bivectors are associated with it differing only by a scalar factor.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] All bivectors can be interpreted as planes, or more precisely as directed plane segments.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In three dimensions, every bivector can be generated by the exterior product of two vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] where θ is the angle between the vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This is the area of the parallelogram with edges **a** and **b**, as shown in the diagram.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] One interpretation is that the area is swept out by **b** as it moves along **a**.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The exterior product is antisymmetric, so reversing the order of **a** and **b** to make **a** move along **b** results in a bivector with the opposite direction that is the negative of the first.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The plane of bivector **a** ∧ **b** contains both **a** and **b** so they are both parallel to the plane.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Bivectors and axial vectors are related as being Hodge dual.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In a real vector space, the Hodge dual relates the blade that represents a subspace to its orthogonal complement, so if a bivector represents a plane then the axial vector associated with it is simply the plane's surface normal.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The plane has two normal sets of vbectors, one on each side, giving the two possible orientations for the plane and bivector.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In three dimensions, Hodge duality relates the cross product to the exterior product.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] It can also be used to represent physical quantities, like torque and angular momentum.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In vector algebra they are usually represented by pseudovectors that are perpendicular to the plane of the force, linear momentum or displacement that they are calculated from.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] But if a bivector is used instead, the plane is the plane of the bivector, so is a more natural way to represent the quantities and the way in which they act.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Unlike the vector representation, it generalises to other dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The geometric product of two bivectors has a geometric interpretation.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In three dimensions it is the same as the angle between the normal vectors dual to the planes, and it generalises to some extent in higher dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Bivectors can be added together as areas.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This can be interpreted geometrically as seen in the diagram: the two areas sum to give a third, with the three areas forming faces of a prism with **a**, **b**, **c** and **b** + **c** as edges.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This only works in three dimensions as it is the only number of dimensions in which a vector that is parallel to both bivectors must exist.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In a higher number of dimensions, bivectors generally are not associated with a single plane, or if they are (simple bivectors), two bivectors may have no vector in common, and so sum to a non-simple bivector.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In four dimensions, the Hodge dual of a bivector is a bivector, and the space ⋀2**R**4 is dual to itself.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Normal vectors are not unique, instead every plane is orthogonal to all the vectors in its Hodge dual space.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This can be used to partition the bivectors into two 'halves', in the following way.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] There are four distinct ways of picking one bivector from each of the first two pairs, and once these first two are picked their sum yields the third bivector from the other pair.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In four dimensions bivectors are generated by the exterior product of vectors in **R**4, but with one important difference from **R**3 and **R**2.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In four dimensions not all bivectors are simple.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] There are bivectors such as **e**12 + **e**34 that cannot be generated by the exterior product of two vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This also means they do not have a real, that is scalar, square.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The element **e**1234 is the pseudoscalar in Cl4, distinct from the scalar, so the square is non-scalar.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] All bivectors in four dimensions can be generated using at most two exterior products and four vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Similarly, every bivector can be written as the sum of two simple bivectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] It is useful to choose two orthogonal bivectors for this, and this is always possible to do.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Moreover, for a generic bivector the choice of simple bivectors is unique, that is, there is only one way to decompose into orthogonal bivectors; the only exception is when the two orthogonal bivectors have equal magnitudes (as in the above example): in this case the decomposition is not unique.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The decomposition is always unique in the case of simple bivectors, with the added bonus that one of the orthogonal parts is zero.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] As in three dimensions bivectors in four dimension generate rotations through the exponential map, and all rotations can be generated this way.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The rotations generated are more complex though.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] rotations are those that fix a plane in 4D, and rotate by an angle "about" this plane.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] rotations have only one fixed point, the origin, and rotate through two angles about two orthogonal planes.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] rotations are double rotations where the angles of rotation are equal.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In this case the planes about which the rotation is taking place are not unique.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] These are generated by bivectors in a straightforward way.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Simple rotations are generated by simple bivectors, with the fixed plane the dual or orthogonal to the plane of the bivector.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The rotation can be said to take place about that plane, in the plane of the bivector.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] All other bivectors generate double rotations, with the two angles of the rotation equalling the magnitudes of the two simple bivectors that the non-simple bivector is composed of.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Isoclinic rotations arise when these magnitudes are equal, in which case the decomposition into two simple bivectors is not unique.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Bivectors in general do not commute, but one exception is orthogonal bivectors and exponents of them.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] It is always possible to do this as all bivectors can be expressed as sums of orthogonal bivectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Spacetime is a mathematical model for our universe used in special relativity.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] It consists of three space dimensions and one time dimension combined into a single four-dimensional space.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] It is naturally described using geometric algebra and bivectors, with the Euclidean metric replaced by a Minkowski metric.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] (Note the order and indices above are not universal – here **e**4 is the time-like dimension).
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The geometric algebra is Cl3,1(**R**), and the subspace of bivectors is ⋀2**R**3,1.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The simple bivectors **e**23, **e**31 and **e**12 have negative squares and span the bivectors of the three-dimensional subspace corresponding to Euclidean space, **R**3.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] These bivectors generate ordinary rotations in **R**3.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The simple bivectors **e**14, **e**24 and **e**34 have positive squares and as planes span a space dimension and the time dimension.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] where **Ω** is the bivector (**e**14, etc.), identified via the metric with an antisymmetric linear transformation of **R**3,1.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] These are Lorentz boosts, expressed in a particularly compact way, using the same kind of algebra as in **R**3 and **R**4.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The set of all rotations in spacetime form the Lorentz group, and from them most of the consequences of special relativity can be deduced.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] More generally this show how transformations in Euclidean space and spacetime can all be described using the same kind of algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Maxwell's equations are used in physics to describe the relationship between electric and magnetic fields.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Normally given as four differential equations they have a particularly compact form when the fields are expressed as a spacetime bivector from ⋀2**R**3,1.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] where **e**4 is again the basis vector for the time-like dimension and c is the speed of light.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The product *B***e**123 yields the bivector that is Hodge dual to *B* in three dimensions, as discussed above, while *E***e**4 as a product of orthogonal vectors is also bivector-valued.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] As a whole it is the electromagnetic tensor expressed more compactly as a bivector, and is used as follows.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] where *j* is current density and ρ is charge density.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The operator ∇ is a differential operator in geometric algebra, acting on the space dimensions and given by ∇**M** = ∇·**M** + ∇∧**M**.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] When applied to vectors ∇·**M** is the divergence and ∇∧**M** is the curl but with a bivector rather than vector result, that is dual in three dimensions to the curl.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] For general quantity **M** they act as grade lowering and raising differential operators.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In particular if **M** is a scalar then this operator is just the gradient, and it can be thought of as a geometric algebraic del operator.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This equation, when decomposed according to geometric algebra, using geometric products which have both grade raising and grade lowering effects, is equivalent to Maxwell's four equations.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] where *A* is the vector magnetic potential and V is the electric potential.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] using the same differential operator *∂*.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] As has been suggested in earlier sections much of geometric algebra generalises well into higher dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The geometric algebra for the real space **R***n* is Cl*n*(**R**), and the subspace of bivectors is ⋀2**R***n*.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The number of simple bivectors needed to form a general bivector rises with the dimension, so for n odd it is (*n* − 1) / 2, for n even it is *n* / 2.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] So for four and five dimensions only two simple bivectors are needed but three are required for six and seven dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] is the sum of three simple bivectors but no less.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] As in four dimensions it is always possible to find orthogonal simple bivectors for this sum.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] is the rotor generated by bivector **B**.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Simple rotations, that take place in a plane of rotation around a fixed blade of dimension (*n* − 2) are generated by simple bivectors, while other bivectors generate more complex rotations which can be described in terms of the simple bivectors they are sums of, each related to a plane of rotation.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] All bivectors can be expressed as the sum of orthogonal and commutative simple bivectors, so rotations can always be decomposed into a set of commutative rotations about the planes associated with these bivectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] The group of the rotors in n dimensions is the spin group, Spin(*n*).
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] One notable feature, related to the number of simple bivectors and so rotation planes, is that in odd dimensions every rotation has a fixed axis – it is misleading to call it an axis of rotation as in higher dimensions rotations are taking place in multiple planes orthogonal to it.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] This is related to bivectors, as bivectors in odd dimensions decompose into the same number of bivectors as the even dimension below, so have the same number of planes, but one extra dimension.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] As each plane generates rotations in two dimensions in odd dimensions there must be one dimension, that is an axis, that is not being rotated.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Bivectors are also related to the rotation matrix in n dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] As in three dimensions the characteristic equation of the matrix can be solved to find the eigenvalues.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In odd dimensions this has one real root, with eigenvector the fixed axis, and in even dimensions it has no real roots, so either all or all but one of the roots are complex conjugate pairs.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] Each pair is associated with a simple component of the bivector associated with the rotation.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In particular, the log of each pair is the magnitude up to a sign, while eigenvectors generated from the roots are parallel to and so can be used to generate the bivector.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p01] In general the eigenvalues and bivectors are unique, and the set of eigenvalues gives the full decomposition into simple bivectors; if roots are repeated then the decomposition of the bivector into simple bivectors is not unique.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] Geometric algebra can be applied to projective geometry in a straightforward way.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] The geometric algebra used is Cl*n*(**R**), *n* ≥ 3, the algebra of the real vector space **R***n*.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] This is used to describe objects in the real projective space **RP***n*−1.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] The non-zero vectors in Cl*n*(**R**) or **R***n* are associated with points in the projective space so vectors that differ only by a scale factor, so their exterior product is zero, map to the same point.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] Non-zero simple bivectors in ⋀2**R***n* represent lines in **RP***n*−1, with bivectors differing only by a (positive or negative) scale factor representing the same line.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] A description of the projective geometry can be constructed in the geometric algebra using basic operations.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] For example, given two distinct points in **RP***n*−1 represented by vectors **a** and **b** the line containing them is given by **a** ∧ **b** (or **b** ∧ **a**).
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] Two lines intersect in a point if **A** ∧ **B** = 0 for their bivectors **A** and **B**.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] The operation "∨" is the meet, which can be defined as above in terms of the join, *J* = **A** ∧ **B** for non-zero **A** ∧ **B**.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] Using these operations projective geometry can be formulated in terms of geometric algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] where the angle brackets denote the scalar part of the geometric product.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] In the same way all projective space operations can be written in terms of geometric algebra, with bivectors representing general lines in projective space, so the whole geometry can be developed using geometric algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] As noted above a bivector can be written as a skew-symmetric matrix, which through the exponential map generates a rotation matrix that describes the same rotation as the rotor, also generated by the exponential map but applied to the vector.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] But it is also used with other bivectors such as the angular velocity tensor and the electromagnetic tensor, respectively a 3×3 and 4×4 skew-symmetric matrix or tensor.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] Real bivectors in ⋀2**R***n* are isomorphic to *n* × *n* skew-symmetric matrices, or alternately to antisymmetric tensors of degree 2 on **R***n*.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] While bivectors are isomorphic to vectors (via the dual) in three dimensions they can be represented by skew-symmetric matrices in any dimension.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] This is useful for relating bivectors to problems described by matrices, so they can be re-cast in terms of bivectors, given a geometric interpretation, then often solved more easily or related geometrically to other bivector problems.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] More generally, every real geometric algebra is isomorphic to a matrix algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] These contain bivectors as a subspace, though often in a way which is not especially useful.
[src:clifford-algebra/bivector-p02] These matrices are mainly of interest as a way of classifying Clifford algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In mathematics, a **Clifford algebra** is an algebra generated by a vector space with a quadratic form, and is a unital associative algebra with the additional structure of a distinguished subspace.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] As *K*-algebras, they generalize the real numbers, complex numbers, quaternions and several other hypercomplex number systems.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The theory of Clifford algebras is intimately connected with the theory of quadratic forms and orthogonal transformations.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Clifford algebras have important applications in a variety of fields including geometry, theoretical physics and digital image processing.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] They are named after the English mathematician William Kingdon Clifford (1845–1879).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The most familiar Clifford algebras, the **orthogonal Clifford algebras**, are also referred to as (*pseudo-*)*Riemannian Clifford algebras*, as distinct from *symplectic Clifford algebras*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] A Clifford algebra is a unital associative algebra that contains and is generated by a vector space *V* over a field *K*, where *V* is equipped with a quadratic form *Q* : *V* → *K*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The idea of being the "freest" or "most general" algebra subject to this identity can be formally expressed through the notion of a universal property, as done below.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Such a basis may be found by orthogonal diagonalization.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The free algebra generated by *V* may be written as the tensor algebra ⨁*n*≥0 *V* ⊗ ⋯ ⊗ *V*, that is, the direct sum of the tensor product of *n* copies of *V* over all *n*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Therefore one obtains a Clifford algebra as the quotient of this tensor algebra by the two-sided ideal generated by elements of the form *v* ⊗ *v* − *Q*(*v*)1 for all elements *v* ∈ *V*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The product induced by the tensor product in the quotient algebra is written using juxtaposition (e.g.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Its associativity follows from the associativity of the tensor product.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The Clifford algebra has a distinguished subspace *V*, being the image of the embedding map.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Such a subspace cannot in general be uniquely determined given only a *K*-algebra that is isomorphic to the Clifford algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Quadratic forms and Clifford algebras in characteristic 2 form an exceptional case in this respect.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Clifford algebras are closely related to exterior algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Indeed, if *Q* = 0 then the Clifford algebra Cl(*V*, *Q*) is just the exterior algebra ⋀*V*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Whenever 2 is invertible in the ground field *K*, there exists a canonical *linear* isomorphism between ⋀*V* and Cl(*V*, *Q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] That is, they are naturally isomorphic as vector spaces, but with different multiplications (in the case of characteristic two, they are still isomorphic as vector spaces, just not naturally).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Clifford multiplication together with the distinguished subspace is strictly richer than the exterior product since it makes use of the extra information provided by *Q*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The Clifford algebra is a filtered algebra; the associated graded algebra is the exterior algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] More precisely, Clifford algebras may be thought of as *quantizations* (cf. quantum group) of the exterior algebra, in the same way that the Weyl algebra is a quantization of the symmetric algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Weyl algebras and Clifford algebras admit a further structure of a *-algebra, and can be unified as even and odd terms of a superalgebra, as discussed in CCR and CAR algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Let *V* be a vector space over a field *K*, and let *Q* : *V* → *K* be a quadratic form on *V*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In most cases of interest the field *K* is either the field of real numbers **R**, or the field of complex numbers **C**, or a finite field.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] A Clifford algebra as described above always exists and can be constructed as follows: start with the most general algebra that contains *V*, namely the tensor algebra *T*(*V*), and then enforce the fundamental identity by taking a suitable quotient.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The ring product inherited by this quotient is sometimes referred to as the **Clifford product** to distinguish it from the exterior product and the scalar product.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] It is then straightforward to show that Cl(*V*, *Q*) contains *V* and satisfies the above universal property, so that Cl is unique up to a unique isomorphism; thus one speaks of "the" Clifford algebra Cl(*V*, *Q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] It also follows from this construction that *i* is injective.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] One usually drops the *i* and considers *V* as a linear subspace of Cl(*V*, *Q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The universal characterization of the Clifford algebra shows that the construction of Cl(*V*, *Q*) is *functorial* in nature.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Namely, Cl can be considered as a functor from the category of vector spaces with quadratic forms (whose morphisms are linear maps that preserve the quadratic form) to the category of associative algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The universal property guarantees that linear maps between vector spaces (that preserve the quadratic form) extend uniquely to algebra homomorphisms between the associated Clifford algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Since *V* comes equipped with a quadratic form *Q*, in characteristic not equal to 2 there exist bases for *V* that are orthogonal.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] This makes manipulation of orthogonal basis vectors quite simple.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Given a product $e_{i_{1}}e_{i_{2}}\cdots e_{i_{k}}$ of *distinct* orthogonal basis vectors of *V*, one can put them into a standard order while including an overall sign determined by the number of pairwise swaps needed to do so (i.e. the signature of the ordering permutation).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The empty product (*k* = 0) is defined as being the multiplicative identity element.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The most important Clifford algebras are those over real and complex vector spaces equipped with nondegenerate quadratic forms.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Each of the algebras Cl*p*,*q*(**R**) and Cl*n*(**C**) is isomorphic to *A* or *A* ⊕ *A*, where *A* is a full matrix ring with entries from **R**, **C**, or **H**.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] For a complete classification of these algebras see *Classification of Clifford algebras*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Clifford algebras are also sometimes referred to as geometric algebras, most often over the real numbers.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Every nondegenerate quadratic form on a finite-dimensional real vector space is equivalent to the standard diagonal form: $Q(v)=v_{1}^{2}+\dots +v_{p}^{2}-v_{p+1}^{2}-\dots -v_{p+q}^{2},$ where *n* = *p* + *q* is the dimension of the vector space.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The pair of integers (*p*, *q*) is called the signature of the quadratic form.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The real vector space with this quadratic form is often denoted **R***p*,*q*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The symbol Cl*n*(**R**) means either Cl*n*,0(**R**) or Cl0,*n*(**R**), depending on whether the author prefers positive-definite or negative-definite spaces.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] A standard basis {*e*1, ..., *e**n*} for **R***p*,*q* consists of *n* = *p* + *q* mutually orthogonal vectors, *p* of which square to +1 and *q* of which square to −1.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Of such a basis, the algebra Cl*p*,*q*(**R**) will therefore have *p* vectors that square to +1 and *q* vectors that square to −1.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] One can also study Clifford algebras on complex vector spaces.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] We will denote the Clifford algebra on **C***n* with the standard quadratic form by Cl*n*(**C**).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] where M*n*(**C**) denotes the algebra of *n* × *n* matrices over **C**.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In this section, Hamilton's quaternions are constructed as the even subalgebra of the Clifford algebra Cl3,0(**R**).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Let the vector space *V* be real three-dimensional space **R**3, and the quadratic form be the usual quadratic form.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In this section, dual quaternions are constructed as the even subalgebra of a Clifford algebra of real four-dimensional space with a degenerate quadratic form.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Let the vector space *V* be real four-dimensional space **R**4, and let the quadratic form *Q* be a degenerate form derived from the Euclidean metric on **R**3.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] For *v*, *w* in **R**4 introduce the degenerate bilinear form $d(v,w)=v_{1}w_{1}+v_{2}w_{2}+v_{3}w_{3}.$ This degenerate scalar product projects distance measurements in **R**4 onto the **R**3 hyperplane.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The Clifford product of vectors *v* and *w* is given by $vw+wv=-2\,d(v,w).$ Note the negative sign is introduced to simplify the correspondence with quaternions.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The general element of the Clifford algebra Cl(**R**4, *d*) has 16 components.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Let *K* be any field of characteristic not 2.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] For dim *V* = 1, if *Q* has diagonalization diag(*a*), a non-zero vector *x* such that *Q*(*x*) = *a*, then Cl(*V*, *Q*) is algebra-isomorphic to a *K*-algebra generated by an element *x* that satisfies *x*2 = *a*, the quadratic algebra *K*[*X*] / (*X*2 − *a*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In particular, if *a* = 0 (that is, *Q* is the zero quadratic form) then Cl(*V*, *Q*) is algebra-isomorphic to the dual numbers algebra over *K*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Otherwise, Cl(*V*, *Q*) is isomorphic to the quadratic field extension *K*(√*a*) of *K*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] For dim *V* = 2, if *Q* has diagonalization diag(*a*, *b*) with non-zero *a* and *b* (which always exists if *Q* is non-degenerate), then Cl(*V*, *Q*) is isomorphic to a *K*-algebra generated by elements *x* and *y* that satisfies *x*2 = *a*, *y*2 = *b* and *xy* = −*yx*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Thus Cl(*V*, *Q*) is isomorphic to the (generalized) quaternion algebra (*a*, *b*)*K*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Given a vector space *V*, one can construct the exterior algebra ⋀*V*, whose definition is independent of any quadratic form on *V*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] It turns out that if *K* does not have characteristic 2 then there is a natural isomorphism between ⋀*V* and Cl(*V*, *Q*) considered as vector spaces (and there exists an isomorphism in characteristic two, which may not be natural).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] This is an algebra isomorphism if and only if *Q* = 0.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] One can thus consider the Clifford algebra Cl(*V*, *Q*) as an enrichment (or more precisely, a quantization, cf. the Introduction) of the exterior algebra on *V* with a multiplication that depends on *Q* (one can still define the exterior product independently of *Q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The easiest way to establish the isomorphism is to choose an *orthogonal* basis {*e*1, ..., *e**n*} for *V* and extend it to a basis for Cl(*V*, *Q*) as described above.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] One can show that this map is independent of the choice of orthogonal basis and so gives a natural isomorphism.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] If the characteristic of *K* is 0, one can also establish the isomorphism by antisymmetrizing.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Since *f**k* is alternating, it induces a unique linear map ⋀*k* *V* → Cl(*V*, *Q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The direct sum of these maps gives a linear map between ⋀*V* and Cl(*V*, *Q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] This map can be shown to be a linear isomorphism, and it is natural.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] A more sophisticated way to view the relationship is to construct a filtration on Cl(*V*, *Q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Recall that the tensor algebra *T*(*V*) has a natural filtration: *F*0 ⊂ *F*1 ⊂ *F*2 ⊂ ⋯, where *F**k* contains sums of tensors with order ≤ *k*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Projecting this down to the Clifford algebra gives a filtration on Cl(*V*, *Q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The associated graded algebra $\operatorname {Gr} _{F}\operatorname {Cl} (V,Q)=\bigoplus _{k}F^{k}/F^{k-1}$ is naturally isomorphic to the exterior algebra ⋀*V*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Since the associated graded algebra of a filtered algebra is always isomorphic to the filtered algebra as filtered vector spaces (by choosing complements of *Fk* in *F**k*+1 for all *k*), this provides an isomorphism (although not a natural one) in any characteristic, even two.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In the following, assume that the characteristic is not 2.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Clifford algebras are **Z**2-graded algebras (also known as superalgebras).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Since *α* is an automorphism it follows that: $\operatorname {Cl} ^{[i]}(V,Q)\operatorname {Cl} ^{[j]}(V,Q)=\operatorname {Cl} ^{[i+j]}(V,Q)$ where the bracketed superscripts are read modulo 2.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] This gives Cl(*V*, *Q*) the structure of a **Z**2-graded algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The subspace Cl[0](*V*, *Q*) forms a subalgebra of Cl(*V*, *Q*), called the *even subalgebra*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The subspace Cl[1](*V*, *Q*) is called the *odd part* of Cl(*V*, *Q*) (it is not a subalgebra).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] This **Z**2-grading plays an important role in the analysis and application of Clifford algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The automorphism *α* is called the *main involution* or *grade involution*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Elements that are pure in this **Z**2-grading are simply said to be even or odd.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The *degree* of a Clifford number usually refers to the degree in the **Z**-grading.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The even subalgebra Cl[0](*V*, *Q*) of a Clifford algebra is itself isomorphic to a Clifford algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] If *V* is the orthogonal direct sum of a vector *a* of nonzero norm *Q*(*a*) and a subspace *U*, then Cl[0](*V*, *Q*) is isomorphic to Cl(*U*, −*Q*(*a*)*Q*|*U*), where *Q*|*U* is the form *Q* restricted to *U*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Likewise, in the complex case, one can show that the even subalgebra of Cl*n*(**C**) is isomorphic to Cl*n*−1(**C**).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In addition to the automorphism *α*, there are two antiautomorphisms that play an important role in the analysis of Clifford algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The transpose is an antiautomorphism: (*xy*)t = *y*t *x*t.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The transpose operation makes no use of the **Z**2-grading so we define a second antiautomorphism by composing *α* and the transpose.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] We call this operation *Clifford conjugation* denoted ${\bar {x}}$ ${\bar {x}}=\alpha (x^{\mathrm {t} })=\alpha (x)^{\mathrm {t} }.$ Of the two antiautomorphisms, the transpose is the more fundamental.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Note that all of these operations are involutions.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] One can show that they act as ±1 on elements that are pure in the **Z**-grading.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In fact, all three operations depend on only the degree modulo 4.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] When the characteristic is not 2, the quadratic form *Q* on *V* can be extended to a quadratic form on all of Cl(*V*, *Q*) (which we also denoted by *Q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] A basis-independent definition of one such extension is $Q(x)=\left\langle x^{\mathrm {t} }x\right\rangle _{0}$ where ⟨*a*⟩0 denotes the scalar part of *a* (the degree-0 part in the **Z**-grading).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] One can show that $Q(v_{1}v_{2}\cdots v_{k})=Q(v_{1})Q(v_{2})\cdots Q(v_{k})$ where the *vi* are elements of *V* – this identity is *not* true for arbitrary elements of Cl(*V*, *Q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The associated symmetric bilinear form on Cl(*V*, *Q*) is given by $\langle x,y\rangle =\left\langle x^{\mathrm {t} }y\right\rangle _{0}.$ One can check that this reduces to the original bilinear form when restricted to *V*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The bilinear form on all of Cl(*V*, *Q*) is nondegenerate if and only if it is nondegenerate on *V*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The operator of left (respectively right) Clifford multiplication by the transpose *a*t of an element *a* is the adjoint of left (respectively right) Clifford multiplication by *a* with respect to this inner product.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] A central simple algebra over *K* is a matrix algebra over a (finite-dimensional) division algebra with center *K*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] For example, the central simple algebras over the reals are matrix algebras over either the reals or the quaternions.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The structure of Clifford algebras can be worked out explicitly using the following result.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Suppose that *U* has even dimension and a non-singular bilinear form with discriminant *d*, and suppose that *V* is another vector space with a quadratic form.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The Clifford algebra of *U* + *V* is isomorphic to the tensor product of the Clifford algebras of *U* and (−1)dim(*U*)/2*dV*, which is the space *V* with its quadratic form multiplied by (−1)dim(*U*)/2*d*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Notably, the Morita equivalence class of a Clifford algebra (its representation theory: the equivalence class of the category of modules over it) depends on only the signature (*p* − *q*) mod 8.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] This is an algebraic form of Bott periodicity.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Clifford groups or Clifford–Lipschitz groups) was discovered by Rudolf Lipschitz.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In this section we assume that *V* is finite-dimensional and the quadratic form *Q* is nondegenerate.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] An action on the elements of a Clifford algebra by its group of units may be defined in terms of a twisted conjugation: twisted conjugation by *x* maps *y* ↦ *α*(*x*) *y* *x*−1, where *α* is the *main involution* defined above.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] This formula also defines an action of the Lipschitz group on the vector space *V* that preserves the quadratic form *Q*, and so gives a homomorphism from the Lipschitz group to the orthogonal group.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The Lipschitz group contains all elements *r* of *V* for which *Q*(*r*) is invertible in *K*, and these act on *V* by the corresponding reflections that take *v* to *v* − (⟨*r*, *v*⟩ + ⟨*v*, *r*⟩)*r*‍/‍*Q*(*r*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] If *V* is a finite-dimensional vector space with a non-degenerate quadratic form then the Lipschitz group maps onto the orthogonal group of *V* with respect to the form (by the Cartan–Dieudonné theorem) and the kernel consists of the nonzero elements of the field *K*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Over other fields or with indefinite forms, the map is not in general onto, and the failure is captured by the spinor norm.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In arbitrary characteristic, the spinor norm *Q* is defined on the Lipschitz group by $Q(x)=x^{\mathrm {t} }x.$ It is a homomorphism from the Lipschitz group to the group *K*× of non-zero elements of *K*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] It coincides with the quadratic form *Q* of *V* when *V* is identified with a subspace of the Clifford algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Several authors define the spinor norm slightly differently, so that it differs from the one here by a factor of −1, 2, or −2 on Γ1.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The difference is not very important in characteristic other than 2.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The nonzero elements of *K* have spinor norm in the group (*K*×)2 of squares of nonzero elements of the field *K*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] So when *V* is finite-dimensional and non-singular we get an induced map from the orthogonal group of *V* to the group *K*×‍/‍(*K*×)2, also called the spinor norm.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The spinor norm of the reflection about *r*⊥, for any vector *r*, has image *Q*(*r*) in *K*×‍/‍(*K*×)2, and this property uniquely defines it on the orthogonal group.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Note that in characteristic 2 the group {±1} has just one element.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] From the point of view of Galois cohomology of algebraic groups, the spinor norm is a connecting homomorphism on cohomology.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In this section we assume that *V* is finite-dimensional and its bilinear form is non-singular.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The pin group Pin*V*(*K*) is the subgroup of the Lipschitz group Γ of elements of spinor norm 1, and similarly the spin group Spin*V*(*K*) is the subgroup of elements of Dickson invariant 0 in Pin*V*(*K*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] When the characteristic is not 2, these are the elements of determinant 1.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The spin group usually has index 2 in the pin group.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Recall from the previous section that there is a homomorphism from the Lipschitz group onto the orthogonal group.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] We define the special orthogonal group to be the image of Γ0.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] If *K* does not have characteristic 2 this is just the group of elements of the orthogonal group of determinant 1.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] If *K* does have characteristic 2, then all elements of the orthogonal group have determinant 1, and the special orthogonal group is the set of elements of Dickson invariant 0.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] There is a homomorphism from the pin group to the orthogonal group.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The image consists of the elements of spinor norm 1 ∈ *K*×‍/‍(*K*×)2.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The kernel consists of the elements +1 and −1, and has order 2 unless *K* has characteristic 2.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Similarly there is a homomorphism from the Spin group to the special orthogonal group of *V*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In the common case when *V* is a positive or negative definite space over the reals, the spin group maps onto the special orthogonal group, and is simply connected when *V* has dimension at least 3.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Further the kernel of this homomorphism consists of 1 and −1.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] So in this case the spin group, Spin(*n*), is a double cover of SO(*n*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Note, however, that the simple connectedness of the spin group is not true in general: if *V* is **R***p*,*q* for *p* and *q* both at least 2 then the spin group is not simply connected.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In this case the algebraic group Spin*p*,*q* is simply connected as an algebraic group, even though its group of real valued points Spin*p*,*q*(**R**) is not simply connected.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] This is a rather subtle point, which completely confused the authors of at least one standard book about spin groups.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Clifford algebras Cl*p*,*q*(**C**), with *p* + *q* = 2*n* even, are matrix algebras that have a complex representation of dimension 2*n*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] By restricting to the group Pin*p*,*q*(**R**) we get a complex representation of the Pin group of the same dimension, called the spin representation.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] If we restrict this to the spin group Spin*p*,*q*(**R**) then it splits as the sum of two *half spin representations* (or *Weyl representations*) of dimension 2*n*−1.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] If *p* + *q* = 2*n* + 1 is odd then the Clifford algebra Cl*p*,*q*(**C**) is a sum of two matrix algebras, each of which has a representation of dimension 2*n*, and these are also both representations of the pin group Pin*p*,*q*(**R**).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] On restriction to the spin group Spin*p*,*q*(**R**) these become isomorphic, so the spin group has a complex spinor representation of dimension 2*n*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] For examples over the reals see the article on spinors.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] To describe the real spin representations, one must know how the spin group sits inside its Clifford algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The spin group consists of those elements of Pin*p*,*q* that are products of an even number of unit vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Thus by the Cartan–Dieudonné theorem Spin is a cover of the group of proper rotations SO(*p*, *q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Let *α* : Cl → Cl be the automorphism that is given by the mapping *v* ↦ −*v* acting on pure vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Then in particular, Spin*p*,*q* is the subgroup of Pin*p*,*q* whose elements are fixed by *α*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Let $\operatorname {Cl} _{p,q}^{[0]}=\{x\in \operatorname {Cl} _{p,q}\mid \alpha (x)=x\}.$ (These are precisely the elements of even degree in Cl*p*,*q*.) Then the spin group lies within Cl[0] *p*,*q*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The irreducible representations of Cl*p*,*q* restrict to give representations of the pin group.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Conversely, since the pin group is generated by unit vectors, all of its irreducible representation are induced in this manner.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] For the same reasons, the irreducible representations of the spin coincide with the irreducible representations of Cl[0] *p*,*q*.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] To classify the pin representations, one need only appeal to the classification of Clifford algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] One of the principal applications of the exterior algebra is in differential geometry where it is used to define the bundle of differential forms on a smooth manifold.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] In the case of a (pseudo-)Riemannian manifold, the tangent spaces come equipped with a natural quadratic form induced by the metric.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Thus, one can define a Clifford bundle in analogy with the exterior bundle.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] This has a number of important applications in Riemannian geometry.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Perhaps more important is the link to a spin manifold, its associated spinor bundle and spinc manifolds.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Clifford algebras have numerous important applications in physics.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] These are exactly the defining relations for the Clifford algebra Cl 1,3(**R**), whose complexification is Cl 1,3(**R**)**C**, which, by the classification of Clifford algebras, is isomorphic to the algebra of 4 × 4 complex matrices Cl4(**C**) ≈ M4(**C**).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] However, it is best to retain the notation Cl 1,3(**R**)**C**, since any transformation that takes the bilinear form to the canonical form is *not* a Lorentz transformation of the underlying spacetime.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The Clifford algebra of spacetime used in physics thus has more structure than Cl4(**C**).
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] It has in addition a set of preferred transformations – Lorentz transformations.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The Dirac matrices were first written down by Paul Dirac when he was trying to write a relativistic first-order wave equation for the electron, and give an explicit isomorphism from the Clifford algebra to the algebra of complex matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The result was used to define the Dirac equation and introduce the Dirac operator.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The entire Clifford algebra shows up in quantum field theory in the form of Dirac field bilinears.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The use of Clifford algebras to describe quantum theory has been advanced among others by Mario Schönberg, by David Hestenes in terms of geometric calculus, by David Bohm and Basil Hiley and co-workers in form of a hierarchy of Clifford algebras, and by Elio Conte et al.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Clifford algebras have been applied in the problem of action recognition and classification in computer vision.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Rodriguez et al propose a Clifford embedding to generalize traditional MACH filters to video (3D spatiotemporal volume), and vector-valued data such as optical flow.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Vector-valued data is analyzed using the Clifford Fourier Transform.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] Based on these vectors action filters are synthesized in the Clifford Fourier domain and recognition of actions is performed using Clifford correlation.
[src:clifford-algebra/clifford-algebra] The authors demonstrate the effectiveness of the Clifford embedding by recognizing actions typically performed in classic feature films and sports broadcast television.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] When interpreted as the matrices of the action of a set of orthogonal basis vectors for contravariant vectors in Minkowski space, the column vectors on which the matrices act become a space of spinors, on which the Clifford algebra of spacetime acts.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] This in turn makes it possible to represent infinitesimal spatial rotations and Lorentz boosts.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] Spinors facilitate spacetime computations in general, and in particular are fundamental to the Dirac equation for relativistic spin ${\tfrac {\ 1\ }{2}}$ particles.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] Gamma matrices were introduced by Paul Dirac in 1928.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] $\gamma ^{0}$ is the time-like, Hermitian matrix.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The other three are space-like, anti-Hermitian matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] More compactly, $\ \gamma ^{0}=\sigma ^{3}\otimes I_{2}\ ,$ and $\ \gamma ^{j}=i\sigma ^{2}\otimes \sigma ^{j}\ ,$ where $\ \otimes \$ denotes the Kronecker product and the $\ \sigma ^{j}\$ (for j = 1, 2, 3) denote the Pauli matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The "fifth matrix" $\ \gamma ^{5}\$ is not a proper member of the main set of four; it is used for separating nominal left and right chiral representations.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The gamma matrices have a group structure, the gamma group, that is shared by all matrix representations of the group, in any dimension, for any signature of the metric.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] For example, the 2×2 Pauli matrices are a set of "gamma" matrices in three dimensional space with metric of Euclidean signature (3, 0).
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] In five spacetime dimensions, the four gammas, above, together with the fifth gamma-matrix to be presented below generate the Clifford algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] where the curly brackets $\ \{,\}\$ represent the anticommutator, $\ \eta _{\mu \nu }\$ is the Minkowski metric with signature (+ − − −), and $I_{4}$ is the 4 × 4 identity matrix.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] This defining property is more fundamental than the numerical values used in the specific representation of the gamma matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] or a multiplication of all gamma matrices by i , which of course changes their hermiticity properties detailed below.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] More simply, given a basis for *V*, $\ \mathrm {Cl} _{1,3}(\mathbb {R} )_{\mathbb {C} }\$ is just the set of all 4×4 complex matrices, but endowed with a Clifford algebra structure.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] Spacetime is assumed to be endowed with the Minkowski metric ημν.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] A space of Dirac spinors, Ux , is also assumed at every point in spacetime, endowed with the Dirac spinor representation of the Lorentz group.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The Dirac spinor fields Ψ of the Dirac equations, evaluated at any point x in spacetime, are elements of Ux (see below).
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The Clifford algebra is assumed to act on Ux as well (by matrix multiplication with column vectors Ψ(*x*) in Ux for all x).
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] This will be the primary view of elements of $\ \mathrm {Cl} _{1,3}(\mathbb {R} )_{\mathbb {C} }\$ in this section.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] showing that the quantity of γμ can be viewed as a *basis* of a representation space of the 4 vector representation of the Lorentz group sitting inside the Clifford algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The last identity can be recognized as the defining relationship for matrices belonging to an indefinite orthogonal group, which is $\ \eta \Lambda ^{\textsf {T}}\eta =\Lambda ^{-1}\ ,$ written in indexed notation.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] should be treated as 4 vectors in manipulations.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] It also means that indices can be raised and lowered on the γ using the metric ημν as with any 4 vector.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The notation is called the Feynman slash notation.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The slash operation maps the basis eμ of V, or any 4 dimensional vector space, to basis vectors γμ.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] This is different from the transformation rule for the γμ, which are now treated as (fixed) basis vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The designation of the 4 tuple $\left(\gamma ^{\mu }\right)_{\mu =0}^{3}=\left(\gamma ^{0},\gamma ^{1},\gamma ^{2},\gamma ^{3}\right)$ as a 4 vector sometimes found in the literature is thus a slight misnomer.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The latter transformation corresponds to an active transformation of the components of a slashed quantity in terms of the basis γμ, and the former to a passive transformation of the basis γμ itself.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The elements $\ \sigma ^{\mu \nu }=\gamma ^{\mu }\gamma ^{\nu }-\gamma ^{\nu }\gamma ^{\mu }\$ form a representation of the Lie algebra of the Lorentz group.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] When these matrices, and linear combinations of them, are exponentiated, they are Dirac spinor representations of the Lorentz group, e.g., the S(Λ) of above are of this form.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The 6 dimensional space the *σμν* span is the representation space of a tensor representation of the Lorentz group.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] For the higher order elements of the Clifford algebra in general and their transformation rules, see the article Dirac algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The spin representation of the Lorentz group is encoded in the spin group Spin(1, 3) (for real, uncharged spinors) and in the complexified spin group Spin(1, 3) for charged (Dirac) spinors.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] Although $\ \gamma ^{5}\$ uses the letter gamma, it is not one of ***the*** gamma matrices of $\ \mathrm {Cl} _{1,3}(\mathbb {R} )~.$ The index number 5 is a relic of old notation: $\ \gamma ^{0}\$ used to be called " $\gamma ^{4}$ ".
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] where $\delta _{\mu \nu \varrho \sigma }^{\alpha \beta \gamma \delta }$ is the type (4,4) generalized Kronecker delta in 4 dimensions, in full antisymmetrization.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] If $\ \varepsilon _{\alpha \dots \beta }\$ denotes the Levi-Civita symbol in n dimensions, we can use the identity $\delta _{\mu \nu \varrho \sigma }^{\alpha \beta \gamma \delta }=-\varepsilon ^{\alpha \beta \gamma \delta }\varepsilon _{\mu \nu \varrho \sigma }$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] This matrix is useful in discussions of quantum mechanical chirality.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The Clifford algebra in odd dimensions behaves like *two* copies of the Clifford algebra of one less dimension, a left copy and a right copy.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] Thus, one can employ a bit of a trick to repurpose i *γ* 5 as one of the generators of the Clifford algebra in five dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] In this case, the set {*γ* 0, *γ* 1, *γ* 2, *γ* 3, *i γ* 5} therefore, by the last two properties (keeping in mind that *i* 2 ≡ −1) and those of the ‘old’ gammas, forms the basis of the Clifford algebra in 5 spacetime dimensions for the metric signature (1,4). .
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] In metric signature (4,1), the set {*γ* 0, *γ* 1, *γ* 2, *γ* 3, *γ* 5} is used, where the *γ* *μ* are the appropriate ones for the (3,1) signature.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] This pattern is repeated for spacetime dimension 2*n* even and the next odd dimension 2*n* + 1 for all *n* ≥ 1.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] For more detail, see higher-dimensional gamma matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The following identities follow from the fundamental anticommutation relation, so they hold in any basis (although the last one depends on the sign choice for $\gamma ^{5}$ ).
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The gamma matrices can be chosen with extra hermiticity conditions which are restricted by the above anticommutation relations however.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] One checks immediately that these hermiticity relations hold for the Dirac representation.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The hermiticity conditions are not invariant under the action $\gamma ^{\mu }\to S(\Lambda )\gamma ^{\mu }{S(\Lambda )}^{-1}$ of a Lorentz transformation $\Lambda$ because $S(\Lambda )$ is not necessarily a unitary transformation due to the non-compactness of the Lorentz group.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] where $(\cdot )^{\textsf {T}}$ denotes the matrix transpose.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The explicit form that C takes is dependent on the specific representation chosen for the gamma matrices, up to an arbitrary phase factor.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] This is because although charge conjugation is an automorphism of the gamma group, it is *not* an inner automorphism (of the group).
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] Conjugating matrices can be found, but they are representation-dependent.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The charge conjugation operator is also unitary $C^{-1}=C^{\dagger }$ , while for $\mathrm {Cl} _{1,3}(\mathbb {R} )$ it also holds that $C^{\textsf {T}}=-C$ for any representation.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] Given a representation of gamma matrices, the arbitrary phase factor for the charge conjugation operator can not always be chosen such that $C^{\dagger }=C^{\textsf {T}}$ , as is the case for the common four representations given below, known as Dirac, chiral and Majorana representation.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] Many follow directly from expanding out the slash notation and contracting expressions of the form $\ a_{\mu }b_{\nu }c_{\rho }\ \ldots \$ with the appropriate identity in terms of gamma matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] where *k* runs from 1 to 3 and the σk are Pauli matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The gamma matrices we have written so far are appropriate for acting on Dirac spinors written in the *Dirac basis*; in fact, the Dirac basis is defined by these matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The idempotence of the chiral projections is manifest.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] where now $\psi _{\mathrm {L} }$ and $\psi _{\mathrm {R} }$ are left-handed and right-handed two-component Weyl spinors.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] where $\psi _{\mathrm {L} }$ and $\psi _{\mathrm {R} }$ are the left-handed and right-handed two-component Weyl spinors, as before.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] There is also the Majorana basis, in which all of the Dirac matrices are imaginary, and the spinors and Dirac equation are real.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] where C is the charge conjugation matrix, which matches the Dirac version defined above.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The reason for making all gamma matrices imaginary is solely to obtain the particle physics metric (+, −, −, −), in which squared masses are positive.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The Majorana representation, however, is real.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] One can factor out the $\ i\$ to obtain a different representation with four component real spinors and real gamma matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The consequence of removing the $\ i\$ is that the only possible metric with real gamma matrices is (−, +, +, +).
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] Cl1,3( $\mathbb {R}$ ) differs from Cl1,3( $\mathbb {C}$ ): in Cl1,3( $\mathbb {R}$ ) only *real* linear combinations of the gamma matrices and their products are allowed.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] As *Clifford algebras*, Cl1,3( $\mathbb {C}$ ) and Cl4( $\mathbb {C}$ ) are isomorphic, see classification of Clifford algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The reason is that the underlying signature of the spacetime metric loses its signature (1,3) upon passing to the complexification.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] However, the transformation required to bring the bilinear form to the complex canonical form is not a Lorentz transformation and hence not "permissible" (at the very least impractical) since all physics is tightly knit to the Lorentz symmetry and it is preferable to keep it manifest.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] Proponents of geometric algebra strive to work with real algebras wherever that is possible.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] They argue that it is generally possible (and usually enlightening) to identify the presence of an imaginary unit in a physical equation.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] Such units arise from one of the many quantities in a real Clifford algebra that square to −1, and these have geometric significance because of the properties of the algebra and the interaction of its various subspaces.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] Some of these proponents also question whether it is necessary or even useful to introduce an additional imaginary unit in the context of the Dirac equation.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] In the mathematics of Riemannian geometry, it is conventional to define the Clifford algebra Clp,q( $\mathbb {R}$ ) for arbitrary dimensions p,q.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The Weyl spinors transform under the action of the spin group $\mathrm {Spin} (n)$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The $\times _{\mathbb {Z} _{2}}$ is entangling parity and charge conjugation in a manner suitable for relating the Dirac particle/anti-particle states (equivalently, the chiral states in the Weyl basis).
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The Dirac spinor, insofar as it has linearly independent left and right components, can interact with the electromagnetic field.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] This is in contrast to the Majorana spinor and the ELKO spinor (Eigenspinoren des Ladungskonjugationsoperators), which cannot (*i.e.* they are electrically neutral), as they explicitly constrain the spinor so as to not interact with the $S^{1}$ part coming from the complexification.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] The ELKO spinor is a Lounesto class 5 spinor.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p01] However, in contemporary practice in physics, the Dirac algebra rather than the space-time algebra continues to be the standard environment the spinors of the Dirac equation "live" in.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p02] The gamma matrices are diagonalizable with eigenvalues $\pm 1$ for $\gamma ^{0}$ , and eigenvalues $\pm i$ for $\gamma ^{k}$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p02] In particular, this implies that $\gamma ^{0}$ is simultaneously Hermitian and unitary, while the $\gamma ^{i}$ are simultaneously anti–Hermitian and unitary.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p02] Further, the multiplicity of each eigenvalue is two.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p02] More generally, if $\ \gamma ^{\mu }X_{\mu }\$ is not null, a similar result holds.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p02] For concreteness, we restrict to the positive norm case $\ \gamma ^{\mu }p_{\mu }=p\!\!\!/\$ with $\ p\cdot p=m^{2}>0~.$ The negative case follows similarly.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p02] It follows that the solution space to $\ p\!\!\!/-m=0\$ (that is, the kernel of the left-hand side) has dimension 2.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p02] This means the solution space for plane wave solutions to Dirac's equation has dimension 2.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p02] This result still holds for the massless Dirac equation.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p02] In quantum field theory one can Wick rotate the time axis to transit from Minkowski space to Euclidean space.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p02] This is particularly useful in some renormalization procedures as well as lattice gauge theory.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p02] It is also worth noting that there are variants of this which insert instead $-i$ on one of the matrices, such as in lattice QCD codes which use the chiral basis.
[src:clifford-algebra/gamma-matrices-p02] which is unchanged from its Minkowski version.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In mathematics, a **geometric algebra** (also known as a Clifford algebra) is an algebra that can represent and manipulate geometrical objects such as vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Geometric algebra is built out of two fundamental operations, addition and the **geometric product**.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Multiplication of vectors results in higher-dimensional objects called multivectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Compared to other formalisms for manipulating geometric objects, geometric algebra is noteworthy for supporting vector division (though generally not by all elements) and addition of objects of different dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The geometric product was first briefly mentioned by Hermann Grassmann, who was chiefly interested in developing the closely related exterior algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In 1878, William Kingdon Clifford greatly expanded on Grassmann's work to form what are now usually called Clifford algebras in his honor (although Clifford himself chose to call them "geometric algebras").
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Clifford defined the Clifford algebra and its product as a unification of the Grassmann algebra and Hamilton's quaternion algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Adding the dual of the Grassmann exterior product allows the use of the Grassmann–Cayley algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In the late 1990s, plane-based geometric algebra and conformal geometric algebra (CGA) respectively provided a framework for euclidean geometry and classical geometries.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In practice, these and several derived operations allow a correspondence of elements, subspaces and operations of the algebra with geometric interpretations.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] For several decades, geometric algebras went somewhat ignored, greatly eclipsed by the vector calculus then newly developed to describe electromagnetism.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The term "geometric algebra" was repopularized in the 1960s by David Hestenes, who advocated its importance to relativistic physics.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The scalars and vectors have their usual interpretation and make up distinct subspaces of a geometric algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Bivectors provide a more natural representation of the pseudovector quantities of 3D vector calculus that are derived as a cross product, such as oriented area, oriented angle of rotation, torque, angular momentum and the magnetic field.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A trivector can represent an oriented volume, and so on.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] An element called a blade may be used to represent a subspace and orthogonal projections onto that subspace.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Rotations and reflections are represented as elements.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Unlike a vector algebra, a geometric algebra naturally accommodates any number of dimensions and any quadratic form such as in relativity.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Examples of geometric algebras applied in physics include the spacetime algebra (and the less common algebra of physical space).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Geometric calculus, an extension of GA that incorporates differentiation and integration, can be used to formulate other theories such as complex analysis and differential geometry, e.g. by using the Clifford algebra instead of differential forms.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Geometric algebra has been advocated, most notably by David Hestenes and Chris Doran, as the preferred mathematical framework for physics.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Proponents claim that it provides compact and intuitive descriptions in many areas including classical and quantum mechanics, electromagnetic theory, and relativity.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] GA has also found use as a computational tool in computer graphics and robotics.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] There are a number of different ways to define a geometric algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Hestenes's original approach was axiomatic, "full of geometric significance" and equivalent to the universal Clifford algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The Clifford algebra is commonly defined as a quotient of the tensor algebra of ⁠ V ⁠, though this definition is abstract, so the following definition is presented without requiring abstract algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] To cover degenerate symmetric bilinear forms, the last condition must be modified.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] It can be shown that these conditions uniquely characterize the geometric product.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] For the remainder of this article, only the real case, ⁠ $F=\mathbb {R}$ ⁠, will be considered.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The notation ⁠ ${\mathcal {G}}(p,q)$ ⁠ (respectively ⁠ ${\mathcal {G}}(p,q,r)$ ⁠) will be used to denote a geometric algebra for which the bilinear form ⁠ g ⁠ has the signature ⁠ $(p,q)$ ⁠ (respectively ⁠ $(p,q,r)$ ⁠).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The product in the geometric algebra is called the *geometric product*, and the product in the contained exterior algebra is called the *exterior product* (frequently called the *wedge product* or the *outer product*).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] It is standard to denote these respectively by juxtaposition (i.e., suppressing any explicit multiplication symbol) and the symbol ⁠ $\wedge$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Their connection to the inner product will be elaborated on below.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The above definition of the geometric algebra is still somewhat abstract, so we summarize the properties of the geometric product here.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The exterior product has the same properties, except that the last property above is replaced by ⁠ $a\wedge a=0$ ⁠ for ⁠ $a\in V$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Note that in the last property above, the real number ⁠ $g(a,a)$ ⁠ need not be nonnegative if ⁠ g ⁠ is not positive-definite.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] An important property of the geometric product is the existence of elements that have a multiplicative inverse.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A nonzero element of the algebra does not necessarily have a multiplicative inverse.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] For example, if u is a vector in V such that ⁠ $u^{2}=1$ ⁠, the element $\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}(1+u)$ is both a nontrivial idempotent element and a nonzero zero divisor, and thus has no inverse.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] It is usual to identify $\mathbb {R}$ and V with their images under the natural embeddings $\mathbb {R} \to {\mathcal {G}}(p,q)$ and ⁠ $V\to {\mathcal {G}}(p,q)$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In this article, this identification is assumed.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Throughout, the terms *scalar* and *vector* refer to elements of $\mathbb {R}$ and V respectively (and of their images under this embedding).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Orientation defined by an ordered set of vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Reversed orientation corresponds to negating the exterior product.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Conversely, ⁠ g ⁠ is completely determined by the algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] the ungeneralized or vector form of the geometric product.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The inner and exterior products are associated with familiar concepts from standard vector algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Geometrically, a and b are parallel if their geometric product is equal to their inner product, whereas a and b are perpendicular if their geometric product is equal to their exterior product.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In a geometric algebra for which the square of any nonzero vector is positive, the inner product of two vectors can be identified with the dot product of standard vector algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The exterior product of two vectors can be identified with the signed area enclosed by a parallelogram the sides of which are the vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The cross product of two vectors in 3 dimensions with positive-definite quadratic form is closely related to their exterior product.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Most instances of geometric algebras of interest have a nondegenerate quadratic form.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] If the quadratic form is fully degenerate, the inner product of any two vectors is always zero, and the geometric algebra is then simply an exterior algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Unless otherwise stated, this article will treat only nondegenerate geometric algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] where the sum is over all permutations of the indices, with $\operatorname {sgn} (\sigma )$ the sign of the permutation, and $a_{i}$ are vectors (not general elements of the algebra).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Since every element of the algebra can be expressed as the sum of products of this form, this defines the exterior product for every pair of elements of the algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] It follows from the definition that the exterior product forms an alternating algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] where $\operatorname {Pf} (A)$ is the Pfaffian of ⁠ A ⁠ and ${\textstyle {\mathcal {C}}={\binom {n}{2i}}}$ provides combinations, ⁠ $\mu$ ⁠, of ⁠ n ⁠ indices divided into ⁠ $2i$ ⁠ and ⁠ $n-2i$ ⁠ parts and ⁠ k ⁠ is the parity of the combination.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The Pfaffian provides a metric for the exterior algebra and, as pointed out by Claude Chevalley, Clifford algebra reduces to the exterior algebra with a zero quadratic form.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The role the Pfaffian plays can be understood from a geometric viewpoint by developing Clifford algebra from simplices.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] This derivation provides a better connection between Pascal's triangle and simplices because it provides an interpretation of the first column of ones.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A multivector that is the exterior product of r linearly independent vectors is called a *blade*, and is said to be of grade ⁠ r ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A multivector that is the sum of blades of grade r is called a (homogeneous) multivector of grade ⁠ r ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] From the axioms, with closure, every multivector of the geometric algebra is a sum of blades.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Consider a set of r linearly independent vectors $\{a_{1},\ldots ,a_{r}\}$ spanning an ⁠ r ⁠-dimensional subspace of the vector space.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Since orthogonal transformations preserve inner products, it follows that $e_{i}\cdot e_{j}=[\mathbf {D} ]_{ij}$ and thus the $\{e_{1},\ldots ,e_{r}\}$ are perpendicular.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Therefore, every blade of grade r can be written as the exterior product of r vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] More generally, if a degenerate geometric algebra is allowed, then the orthogonal matrix is replaced by a block matrix that is orthogonal in the nondegenerate block, and the diagonal matrix has zero-valued entries along the degenerate dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] then these normalized vectors must square to $+1$ or ⁠ $-1$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] By Sylvester's law of inertia, the total number of ⁠ $+1$ ⁠ and the total number of ⁠ $-1$ ⁠s along the diagonal matrix is invariant.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] By extension, the total number p of these vectors that square to $+1$ and the total number q that square to $-1$ is invariant.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] (The total number of basis vectors that square to zero is also invariant, and may be nonzero if the degenerate case is allowed.) We denote this algebra ⁠ ${\mathcal {G}}(p,q)$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] For example, ${\mathcal {G}}(3,0)$ models three-dimensional Euclidean space, ${\mathcal {G}}(1,3)$ relativistic spacetime and ${\mathcal {G}}(4,1)$ a conformal geometric algebra of a three-dimensional space.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The set of all possible products of n orthogonal basis vectors with indices in increasing order, including 1 as the empty product, forms a basis for the entire geometric algebra (an analogue of the PBW theorem).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A basis formed this way is called a **standard basis** for the geometric algebra, and any other orthogonal basis for V will produce another standard basis.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Each standard basis consists of $2^{n}$ elements.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Every multivector of the geometric algebra can be expressed as a linear combination of the standard basis elements.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The terminology " k -vector" is often encountered to describe multivectors containing elements of only one grade.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In higher dimensional space, some such multivectors are not blades (cannot be factored into the exterior product of k vectors).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] By way of example, $e_{1}\wedge e_{2}+e_{3}\wedge e_{4}$ in ${\mathcal {G}}(4,0)$ cannot be factored; typically, however, such elements of the algebra do not yield to geometric interpretation as objects, although they may represent geometric quantities such as rotations.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A ⁠ k ⁠-versor is a multivector that can be expressed as the geometric product of k invertible vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Unit quaternions (originally called versors by Hamilton) may be identified with rotors in 3D space in much the same way as real 2D rotors subsume complex numbers; for the details refer to Dorst.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Some authors use the term "versor product" to refer to the frequently occurring case where an operand is "sandwiched" between operators.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The descriptions for rotations and reflections, including their outermorphisms, are examples of such sandwiching.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] These outermorphisms have a particularly simple algebraic form.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Since both operators and operand are versors there is potential for alternative examples such as rotating a rotor or reflecting a spinor always provided that some geometrical or physical significance can be attached to such operations.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] By the Cartan–Dieudonné theorem we have that every isometry can be given as reflections in hyperplanes and since composed reflections provide rotations then we have that orthogonal transformations are versors.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Clifford group, although Lundholm deprecates this usage).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] We denote the grade involution as ⁠ ${\widehat {S}}$ ⁠ and reversion as ⁠ ${\widetilde {S}}$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Although the Lipschitz group (defined as ⁠ $\{S\in {\mathcal {G}}^{\times }\mid {\widehat {S}}VS^{-1}\subseteq V\}$ ⁠) and the versor group (defined as ⁠ $\textstyle \{\prod _{i=0}^{k}v_{i}\mid v_{i}\in V^{\times },k\in \mathbb {N} \}$ ⁠) have divergent definitions, they are the same group.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Lundholm defines the ⁠ $\operatorname {Pin}$ ⁠, ⁠ $\operatorname {Spin}$ ⁠, and ⁠ $\operatorname {Spin} ^{+}$ ⁠ subgroups of the Lipschitz group.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Multiple analyses of spinors use GA as a representation.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A ⁠ $\mathbb {Z}$ ⁠-graded vector space structure can be established on a geometric algebra by use of the exterior product that is naturally induced by the geometric product.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Since the geometric product and the exterior product are equal on orthogonal vectors, this grading can be conveniently constructed by using an orthogonal basis ⁠ $\{e_{1},\ldots ,e_{n}\}$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Elements of the geometric algebra that are scalar multiples of 1 are of grade 0 and are called *scalars*.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Elements that are in the span of $\{e_{1},\ldots ,e_{n}\}$ are of grade ⁠ 1 ⁠ and are the ordinary vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Elements in the span of $\{e_{i}e_{j}\mid 1\leq i<j\leq n\}$ are of grade 2 and are the bivectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] This terminology continues through to the last grade of ⁠ n ⁠-vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Alternatively, ⁠ n ⁠-vectors are called pseudoscalars, ⁠ $(n-1)$ ⁠-vectors are called pseudovectors, etc.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Many of the elements of the algebra are not graded by this scheme since they are sums of elements of differing grade.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Such elements are said to be of *mixed grade*.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The grading of multivectors is independent of the basis chosen originally.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] This is a grading as a vector space, but not as an algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Because the product of an ⁠ r ⁠-blade and an ⁠ s ⁠-blade is contained in the span of 0 through ⁠ $r+s$ ⁠-blades, the geometric algebra is a filtered algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A multivector A may be decomposed with the **grade-projection operator** ⁠ $\langle A\rangle _{r}$ ⁠, which outputs the grade-⁠ r ⁠ portion of ⁠ A ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] As an example, the geometric product of two vectors $ab=a\cdot b+a\wedge b=\langle ab\rangle _{0}+\langle ab\rangle _{2}$ since $\langle ab\rangle _{0}=a\cdot b$ and $\langle ab\rangle _{2}=a\wedge b$ and ⁠ $\langle ab\rangle _{i}=0$ ⁠, for i other than 0 and ⁠ 2 ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] This is the result of forgetting structure from a ⁠ $\mathrm {Z}$ ⁠-graded vector space to ⁠ $\mathrm {Z} _{2}$ ⁠-graded vector space.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The geometric product respects this coarser grading.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Thus in addition to being a ⁠ $\mathrm {Z} _{2}$ ⁠-graded vector space, the geometric algebra is a ⁠ $\mathrm {Z} _{2}$ ⁠-graded algebra, a.k.a. a superalgebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Restricting to the even part, the product of two even elements is also even.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] This means that the even multivectors defines an *even subalgebra*.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The even subalgebra of an ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional geometric algebra is algebra-isomorphic (without preserving either filtration or grading) to a full geometric algebra of $(n-1)$ dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Geometric algebra represents subspaces of V as blades, and so they coexist in the same algebra with vectors from ⁠ V ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A ⁠ k ⁠-dimensional subspace W of V is represented by taking an orthogonal basis $\{b_{1},b_{2},\ldots ,b_{k}\}$ and using the geometric product to form the blade ⁠ $D=b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{k}$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] There are multiple blades representing ⁠ W ⁠; all those representing W are scalar multiples of ⁠ D ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] These blades can be separated into two sets: positive multiples of D and negative multiples of ⁠ D ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The positive multiples of D are said to have *the same orientation* as ⁠ D ⁠, and the negative multiples the *opposite orientation*.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Blades are important since geometric operations such as projections, rotations and reflections depend on the factorability via the exterior product that (the restricted class of) ⁠ n ⁠-blades provide but that (the generalized class of) grade-⁠ n ⁠ multivectors do not when ⁠ $n\geq 4$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Unit pseudoscalars are blades that play important roles in GA.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A **unit pseudoscalar** for a non-degenerate subspace W of V is a blade that is the product of the members of an orthonormal basis for ⁠ W ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] It can be shown that if I and $I'$ are both unit pseudoscalars for ⁠ W ⁠, then $I=\pm I'$ and ⁠ $I^{2}=\pm 1$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] If one doesn't choose an orthonormal basis for ⁠ W ⁠, then the Plücker embedding gives a vector in the exterior algebra but only up to scaling.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Using the vector space isomorphism between the geometric algebra and exterior algebra, this gives the equivalence class of $\alpha I$ for all ⁠ $\alpha \neq 0$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Orthonormality gets rid of this ambiguity except for the signs above.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Suppose the geometric algebra ${\mathcal {G}}(n,0)$ with the familiar positive definite inner product on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is formed.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Given a plane (two-dimensional subspace) of ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠, one can find an orthonormal basis $\{b_{1},b_{2}\}$ spanning the plane, and thus find a unit pseudoscalar $I=b_{1}b_{2}$ representing this plane.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The geometric product of any two vectors in the span of $b_{1}$ and $b_{2}$ lies in ⁠ $\{\alpha _{0}+\alpha _{1}I\mid \alpha _{i}\in \mathbb {R} \}$ ⁠, that is, it is the sum of a ⁠ 0 ⁠-vector and a ⁠ 2 ⁠-vector.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The resemblance to the imaginary unit is not incidental: the subspace $\{\alpha _{0}+\alpha _{1}I\mid \alpha _{i}\in \mathbb {R} \}$ is ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠-algebra isomorphic to the complex numbers.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In this way, a copy of the complex numbers is embedded in the geometric algebra for each two-dimensional subspace of V on which the quadratic form is definite.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] It is sometimes possible to identify the presence of an imaginary unit in a physical equation.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Such units arise from one of the many quantities in the real algebra that square to ⁠ $-1$ ⁠, and these have geometric significance because of the properties of the algebra and the interaction of its various subspaces.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In ⁠ ${\mathcal {G}}(3,0)$ ⁠, a further familiar case occurs.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Labelling these ⁠ i ⁠, j and k (momentarily deviating from our uppercase convention), the subspace generated by ⁠ 0 ⁠-vectors and ⁠ 2 ⁠-vectors is exactly ⁠ $\{\alpha _{0}+i\alpha _{1}+j\alpha _{2}+k\alpha _{3}\mid \alpha _{i}\in \mathbb {R} \}$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] This set is seen to be the even subalgebra of ⁠ ${\mathcal {G}}(3,0)$ ⁠, and furthermore is isomorphic as an ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠-algebra to the quaternions, another important algebraic system.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] It is common practice to extend the exterior product on vectors to the entire algebra of multivectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] This generalization is consistent with the above definition involving antisymmetrization.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The regressive product is the dual of the exterior product (respectively corresponding to the "meet" and "join" in this context).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The dual specification of elements permits, for blades ⁠ $A_{r}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $B_{s}$ ⁠, the intersection (or meet) where the duality is to be taken relative to a blade containing both ⁠ $A_{r}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $B_{s}$ ⁠ (the smallest such blade being the join).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] with ⁠ I ⁠ the unit pseudoscalar of the algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The regressive product, like the exterior product, is associative.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The inner product on vectors can also be generalized, but in more than one non-equivalent way.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The paper (Dorst 2002) gives a full treatment of several different inner products developed for geometric algebras and their interrelationships, and the notation is taken from there.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Many authors use the same symbol as for the inner product of vectors for their chosen extension (e.g.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The original intention was to make ⁠ $AB=A\cdot B+A\wedge B$ ⁠ true for ⁠ A ⁠ and ⁠ B ⁠ scalars or vectors.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Many authors don't use the restriction of ⁠ $r\neq 0,s\neq 0$ ⁠ in the definition, which is equivalent to the "fat dot" product below.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Dorst (2002) makes an argument for the use of contractions in preference to Hestenes's inner product; they are algebraically more regular and have cleaner geometric interpretations.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A number of identities incorporating the contractions are valid without restriction of their inputs.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Let $\{e_{1},\ldots ,e_{n}\}$ be a basis of ⁠ V ⁠, i.e. a set of n linearly independent vectors that span the ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional vector space ⁠ V ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Given a nondegenerate quadratic form on ⁠ V ⁠, $V^{*}$ becomes naturally identified with ⁠ V ⁠, and the dual basis may be regarded as elements of ⁠ V ⁠, but are not in general the same set as the original basis.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] be the pseudoscalar (which does not necessarily square to ⁠ $\pm 1$ ⁠) formed from the basis ⁠ $\{e_{1},\ldots ,e_{n}\}$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] where the ${\check {e}}_{i}$ denotes that the ⁠ i ⁠th basis vector is omitted from the product.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A dual basis is also known as a reciprocal basis or reciprocal frame.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A major usage of a dual basis is to separate vectors into components.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A dual basis as defined above for the vector subspace of a geometric algebra can be extended to cover the entire algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] For compactness, we'll use a single capital letter to represent an ordered set of vector indices.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Although a versor is easier to work with because it can be directly represented in the algebra as a multivector, versors are a subgroup of linear functions on multivectors, which can still be used when necessary.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The geometric algebra of an ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional vector space is spanned by a basis of $2^{n}$ elements.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] If a multivector is represented by a $2^{n}\times 1$ real column matrix of coefficients of a basis of the algebra, then all linear transformations of the multivector can be expressed as the matrix multiplication by a $2^{n}\times 2^{n}$ real matrix.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] However, such a general linear transformation allows arbitrary exchanges among grades, such as a "rotation" of a scalar into a vector, which has no evident geometric interpretation.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A general linear transformation from vectors to vectors is of interest.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] With the natural restriction to preserving the induced exterior algebra, the *outermorphism* of the linear transformation is the unique extension of the versor.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] for a blade, extended to the whole algebra through linearity.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Although a lot of attention has been placed on CGA, GA is not just one algebra, it is one of a family of algebras with the same essential structure.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In physics, the main applications are the geometric algebra of Minkowski 3+1 spacetime, ⁠ ${\mathcal {G}}(1,3)$ ⁠, called spacetime algebra (STA), or less commonly, ⁠ ${\mathcal {G}}(3,0)$ ⁠, interpreted the algebra of physical space (APS).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] While in STA, points of spacetime are represented simply by vectors, in APS, points of ⁠ $(3+1)$ ⁠-dimensional spacetime are instead represented by paravectors, a three-dimensional vector (space) plus a one-dimensional scalar (time).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In spacetime algebra the electromagnetic field tensor has a bivector representation ⁠ ${F}=({E}+ic{B})\gamma _{0}$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Here, the $i=\gamma _{0}\gamma _{1}\gamma _{2}\gamma _{3}$ is the unit pseudoscalar (or four-dimensional volume element), $\gamma _{0}$ is the unit vector in time direction, and E and B are the classic electric and magnetic field vectors (with a zero time component).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In geometric calculus, juxtaposition of vectors such as in $DF$ indicate the geometric product and can be decomposed into parts as ⁠ $DF=D\cdot F+D\wedge F$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Here D is the covector derivative in any spacetime and reduces to $\nabla$ in flat spacetime.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Where $\bigtriangledown$ plays a role in Minkowski ⁠ 4 ⁠-spacetime which is synonymous to the role of $\nabla$ in Euclidean ⁠ 3 ⁠-space and is related to the d'Alembertian by ⁠ $\Box =\bigtriangledown ^{2}$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The Dirac matrices are a representation of ⁠ ${\mathcal {G}}(1,3)$ ⁠, showing the equivalence with matrix representations used by physicists.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Homogeneous models generally refer to a projective representation in which the elements of the one-dimensional subspaces of a vector space represent points of a geometry.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In a geometric algebra of a space of n dimensions, the rotors represent a set of transformations with $n(n-1)/2$ degrees of freedom, corresponding to rotations – for example, 3 when $n=3$ and 6 when ⁠ $n=4$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Geometric algebra is often used to model a projective space, i.e. as a *homogeneous model*: a point, line, plane, etc. is represented by an equivalence class of elements of the algebra that differ by an invertible scalar factor.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The rotors in a space of dimension $n+1$ have $n(n-1)/2+n$ degrees of freedom, the same as the number of degrees of freedom in the rotations and translations combined for an ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional space.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] This is the case in *Projective Geometric Algebra* (PGA), which is used to represent Euclidean isometries in Euclidean geometry (thereby covering the large majority of engineering applications of geometry).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] In this model, a degenerate dimension is added to the three Euclidean dimensions to form the algebra ⁠ ${\mathcal {G}}(3,0,1)$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] PGA allows projection, meet, and angle formulas to be derived from ${\mathcal {G}}(3,0,1)$ - with a very minor extension to the algebra it is also possible to derive distances and joins.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] PGA is a widely used system that combines geometric algebra with homogeneous representations in geometry, but there exist several other such systems.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] The conformal model discussed below is homogeneous, as is "Conic Geometric Algebra", and see *Plane-based geometric algebra* for discussion of homogeneous models of elliptic and hyperbolic geometry compared with the Euclidean geometry derived from PGA.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Working within GA, Euclidean space $\mathbb {E} ^{3}$ (along with a conformal point at infinity) is embedded projectively in the CGA ${\mathcal {G}}(4,1)$ via the identification of Euclidean points with 1D subspaces in the 4D null cone of the 5D CGA vector subspace.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] This allows all conformal transformations to be performed as rotations and reflections and is covariant, extending incidence relations of projective geometry to rounds objects such as circles and spheres.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] A fast changing and fluid area of GA, CGA is also being investigated for applications to relativistic physics.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p01] Note in this list that ⁠ p ⁠ and ⁠ q ⁠ can be swapped and the same name applies; for example, with *relatively* little change occurring, see sign convention.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] The projection and rejection generalize to null blades B by replacing the inverse $B^{-1}$ with the pseudoinverse $B^{+}$ with respect to the contractive product.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] The outcome of the projection coincides in both cases for non-null blades.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] For null blades ⁠ B ⁠, the definition of the projection given here with the first contraction rather than the second being onto the pseudoinverse should be used, as only then is the result necessarily in the subspace represented by ⁠ B ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] The projection generalizes through linearity to general multivectors ⁠ A ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] The projection is not linear in ⁠ B ⁠ and does not generalize to objects ⁠ B ⁠ that are not blades.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Simple reflections in a hyperplane are readily expressed in the algebra through conjugation with a single vector.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] These serve to generate the group of general rotoreflections and rotations.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] The reflection $c'$ of a vector c along a vector ⁠ m ⁠, or equivalently in the hyperplane orthogonal to ⁠ m ⁠, is the same as negating the component of a vector parallel to ⁠ m ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] This is not the most general operation that may be regarded as a reflection when the dimension ⁠ $n\geq 4$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] A general reflection may be expressed as the composite of any odd number of single-axis reflections.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] where $\alpha$ is the automorphism of reflection through the origin of the vector space (⁠ $v\mapsto -v$ ⁠) extended through linearity to the whole algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] so $Rv{\widetilde {R}}$ leaves the length of v unchanged.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] so the transformation $Rv{\widetilde {R}}$ preserves both length and angle.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] It therefore can be identified as a rotation or rotoreflection; R is called a rotor if it is a proper rotation (as it is if it can be expressed as a product of an even number of vectors) and is an instance of what is known in GA as a *versor*.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] There is a general method for rotating a vector involving the formation of a multivector of the form $R=e^{-B\theta /2}$ that produces a rotation $\theta$ in the plane and with the orientation defined by a ⁠ 2 ⁠-blade ⁠ B ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Rotors are a generalization of quaternions to ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional spaces.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] with the result that ⁠ $a\wedge b$ ⁠ is linear in the product of the "altitude" and the "base" of the parallelogram, that is, its area.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Similar interpretations are true for any number of vectors spanning an ⁠ n ⁠-dimensional parallelotope; the exterior product of vectors ⁠ $a_{1},a_{2},\ldots ,a_{n}$ ⁠, that is ⁠ $\textstyle \bigwedge _{i=1}^{n}a_{i}$ ⁠, has a magnitude equal to the volume of the ⁠ n ⁠-parallelotope.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] An ⁠ n ⁠-vector does not necessarily have a shape of a parallelotope – this is a convenient visualization.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] It could be any shape, although the volume equals that of the parallelotope.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] We may define the line parametrically by ⁠ $p=t+\alpha \ v$ ⁠, where ⁠ p ⁠ and ⁠ t ⁠ are position vectors for points P and T and ⁠ v ⁠ is the direction vector for the line.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] A rotational quantity such as torque or angular momentum is described in geometric algebra as a bivector.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Suppose a circular path in an arbitrary plane containing orthonormal vectors ⁠ ${\widehat {u}}$ ⁠ and ⁠ ${\widehat {\ \!v}}$ ⁠ is parameterized by angle.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] For example, torque is generally defined as the magnitude of the perpendicular force component times distance, or work per unit angle.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Rotational quantities are represented in vector calculus in three dimensions using the cross product.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Unlike the cross product description of torque, ⁠ $\tau =\mathbf {r} \times F$ ⁠, the geometric algebra description does not introduce a vector in the normal direction; a vector that does not exist in two and that is not unique in greater than three dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] The unit bivector describes the plane and the orientation of the rotation, and the sense of the rotation is relative to the angle between the vectors ⁠ ${\widehat {u}}$ ⁠ and ⁠ ${\widehat {\ \!v}}$ ⁠.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Geometric calculus extends the formalism to include differentiation and integration including differential geometry and differential forms.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] as a geometric product, effectively generalizing Stokes' theorem (including the differential form version of it).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] or the fundamental theorem of integral calculus.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Also developed are the concept of vector manifold and geometric integration theory (which generalizes differential forms).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Although the connection of geometry with algebra dates as far back at least to Euclid's *Elements* in the third century B.C.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] (see Greek geometric algebra), GA in the sense used in this article was not developed until 1844, when it was used in a *systematic way* to describe the geometrical properties and *transformations* of a space.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] In that year, Hermann Grassmann introduced the idea of a geometrical algebra in full generality as a certain calculus (analogous to the propositional calculus) that encoded all of the geometrical information of a space.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Grassmann's algebraic system could be applied to a number of different kinds of spaces, the chief among them being Euclidean space, affine space, and projective space.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Following Grassmann, in 1878 William Kingdon Clifford examined Grassmann's algebraic system alongside the quaternions of William Rowan Hamilton in (Clifford 1878).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] From his point of view, the quaternions described certain *transformations* (which he called *rotors*), whereas Grassmann's algebra described certain *properties* (or *Strecken* such as length, area, and volume).
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] His contribution was to define a new product – the *geometric product* – on an existing Grassmann algebra, which realized the quaternions as living within that algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Subsequently, Rudolf Lipschitz in 1886 generalized Clifford's interpretation of the quaternions and applied them to the geometry of rotations in ⁠ n ⁠ dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Later these developments would lead other 20th-century mathematicians to formalize and explore the properties of the Clifford algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Nevertheless, another revolutionary development of the 19th-century would completely overshadow the geometric algebras: that of vector analysis, developed independently by Josiah Willard Gibbs and Oliver Heaviside.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Vector analysis was motivated by James Clerk Maxwell's studies of electromagnetism, and specifically the need to express and manipulate conveniently certain differential equations.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Vector analysis had a certain intuitive appeal compared to the rigors of the new algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Physicists and mathematicians alike readily adopted it as their geometrical toolkit of choice, particularly following the influential 1901 textbook *Vector Analysis* by Edwin Bidwell Wilson, following lectures of Gibbs.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] The legacy of quaternionic analysis in vector analysis can be seen in the use of ⁠ i ⁠, ⁠ j ⁠, ⁠ k ⁠ to indicate the basis vectors of ⁠ $\mathbf {R} ^{3}$ ⁠: it is being thought of as the purely imaginary quaternions.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] From the perspective of geometric algebra, the even subalgebra of the Space Time Algebra is isomorphic to the GA of 3D Euclidean space and quaternions are isomorphic to the even subalgebra of the GA of 3D Euclidean space, which unifies the three approaches.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] Progress on the study of Clifford algebras quietly advanced through the twentieth century, although largely due to the work of abstract algebraists such as Élie Cartan, Hermann Weyl and Claude Chevalley.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] The *geometrical* approach to geometric algebras has seen a number of 20th-century revivals.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] In mathematics, Emil Artin's *Geometric Algebra* discusses the algebra associated with each of a number of geometries, including affine geometry, projective geometry, symplectic geometry, and orthogonal geometry.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] In physics, geometric algebras have been revived as a "new" way to do classical mechanics and electromagnetism, together with more advanced topics such as quantum mechanics and gauge theory.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] David Hestenes reinterpreted the Pauli and Dirac matrices as vectors in ordinary space and spacetime, respectively, and has been a primary contemporary advocate for the use of geometric algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] In computer graphics and robotics, geometric algebras have been revived in order to efficiently represent rotations and other transformations.
[src:clifford-algebra/geometric-algebra-p02] For applications of GA in robotics (screw theory, kinematics and dynamics using versors), computer vision, control and neural computing (geometric learning) see Bayro (2010).
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] In mathematics, the **pin group** is a certain subgroup of the Clifford algebra associated to a quadratic space.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] It maps 2-to-1 to the orthogonal group, just as the spin group maps 2-to-1 to the special orthogonal group.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] In general the map from the Pin group to the orthogonal group is *not* surjective or a universal covering space, but if the quadratic form is definite (and dimension is greater than 2), it is both.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] Let V be a vector space with a non-degenerate quadratic form Q .
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The pin group $\operatorname {Pin} (V,Q)$ is the subset of the Clifford algebra $\operatorname {Cl} (V,Q)$ consisting of elements of the form $v_{1}v_{2}\cdots v_{k}$ , where the $v_{i}$ are vectors such that $Q(v_{i})=\pm 1$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The spin group $\operatorname {Spin} (V,Q)$ is defined similarly, but with k restricted to be even; it is a subgroup of the pin group.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] In this article, V is always a real vector space.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] Geometrically, for vectors v with $Q(v)\neq 0$ , $-vwv^{-1}$ is the reflection of a vector w across the hyperplane orthogonal to v .
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] More generally, an element $v_{1}v_{2}\cdots v_{k}$ of the pin group acts on vectors by transforming w to $(-1)^{k}v_{1}v_{2}\cdots v_{k}w(v_{1}v_{2}\cdots v_{k})^{-1}$ , which is the composition of *k* reflections.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] Since every orthogonal transformation can be expressed as a composition of reflections (the Cartan–Dieudonné theorem), it follows that this representation of the pin group is a homomorphism from the pin group onto the orthogonal group.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] This is often called the twisted adjoint representation.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The elements ±1 of the pin group are the elements which map to the identity $I\in O(p,q)$ , and every element of $O(p,q)$ corresponds to exactly two elements of $\operatorname {Pin} (p,q)$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The pin group of a definite form maps onto the orthogonal group, and each component is simply connected (in dimension 3 and higher): it double covers the orthogonal group.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The pin groups for a positive definite quadratic form *Q* and for its negative −*Q* are not isomorphic, but the orthogonal groups are.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] In terms of the standard forms, O(*n*, 0) = O(0, *n*), but Pin(*n*, 0) and Pin(0, *n*) are in general not isomorphic.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] By contrast, we have the natural isomorphism Spin(*n*, 0) ≅ Spin(0, *n*) and they are both the (unique) non-trivial double cover of the special orthogonal group SO(*n*), which is the (unique) universal cover for *n* ≥ 3.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] Depending on how one counts, and the values of *q* and *p*, there may be as many as thirty-two different double covers of O(*p*, *q*), for *p*, *q* ≠ 0.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] Only two of them are the standard pin groups—those that are contained within the standard Clifford algebra constructions.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] They are called Pin(*p*, *q*) and Pin(*q*, *p*) respectively.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] Not all of these extensions are 'spinoral': one of these double covers, for example, is the trivial extension, which topologically is merely two copies of O(*q*, *p*).
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] For SO(*p*, *q*) when both *p* and *q* are greater than two, the group has 3 unique connected double covers (only one of which is the spin group).
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] Its universal cover is none of these, and is a non-trivial extension of the special orthogonal group by the Klein group, and so is a four fold covering of SO(*p*, *q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The case of *p* or *q* being 2 is complicated (but well understood) by the infinite homotopy group of SO(2).
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] Every connected topological group has a unique universal cover as a topological space, which has a unique group structure as a central extension by the fundamental group.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] In 2001, Andrzej Trautman found the set of all 32 inequivalent double covers of O(*p*) x O(*q*), the maximal compact subgroup of O(*p*, *q*) and an explicit construction of 8 double covers of the same group O(*p*, *q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The group structure on Spin(*V*) (the connected component of determinant 1) is already determined; the group structure on the other component is determined up to the center, and thus has a ±1 ambiguity.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The two extensions are distinguished by whether the preimage of a reflection squares to ±1 ∈ Ker (Spin(*V*) → SO(*V*)), and the two pin groups are named accordingly.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] Concretely, in Pin+, ${\tilde {r}}$ has order 2, and the preimage of a subgroup {1, *r*} is C2 × C2: if one repeats the same reflection twice, one gets the identity.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] In Pin−, ${\tilde {r}}$ has order 4, and the preimage of a subgroup {1, *r*} is C4: if one repeats the same reflection twice, one gets "a rotation by 2π"—the non-trivial element of Spin(*V*) → SO(*V*) can be interpreted as "rotation by 2π" (every axis yields the same element).
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] In 2 dimensions, the distinction between Pin+ and Pin− mirrors the distinction between the dihedral group of a 2*n*-gon and the dicyclic group of the cyclic group C2*n*.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] In Pin+, the preimage of the dihedral group of an *n*-gon, considered as a subgroup Dih*n* < O(2), is the dihedral group of a 2*n*-gon, Dih2*n* < Pin+(2), while in Pin−, the preimage of the dihedral group is the dicyclic group Dic*n* < Pin−(2).
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] In 3 dimensions the situation is as follows.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The Clifford algebra generated by 3 anticommuting square roots of +1 is the algebra of 2×2 complex matrices, and Pin+(3) is isomorphic to $\{A\in U(2):\det A=\pm 1\}$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The Clifford algebra generated by 3 anticommuting square roots of -1 is the algebra $\mathbb {H} \oplus \mathbb {H}$ , and Pin−(3) is isomorphic to SU(2) × C2.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] These groups are nonisomorphic because the center of Pin+(3) is C4 while the center of Pin−(3) is C2 × C2.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] For real (as opposed to complex) compact Pin groups, the center depends upon the dimension n of the relevant vector space, modulo four.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] If $n=2k$ is even, the Clifford algebra is central simple, and as such the center of either $\mathrm {Pin}$ group can only be $\mathrm {C} _{2}$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] In the indefinite case for $\mathrm {Pin} (p,q)$ where $n=p+q$ , one has the same situation but determined instead by $(p-q)\operatorname {mod} 8$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The even dimensional case is as before: when $(p-q)\operatorname {mod} 2=0$ the algebra is central simple, and so the Pin group has a center of $\mathrm {C} _{2}$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The case of opposite signature is simply swapping *p* and *q*, and repeating the above.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] In the odd dimensional case, if one signature has center $\mathrm {C} _{4}$ , the other signature has center $\mathrm {C} _{2}\times \mathrm {C} _{2}$ , and vice versa.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] That is to say, pre-images of the center of the orthogonal group, need only commute or anti-commute with every element of the Pin group.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] The name was introduced in (Atiyah, Bott & Shapiro 1964, page 3, line 17), where they state "This joke is due to J-P.
[src:clifford-algebra/pin-group] It is a back-formation from Spin: "Pin is to O(*n*) as Spin is to SO(*n*)", hence dropping the "S" from "Spin" yields "Pin".
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In geometry and physics, **spinors** (pronounced "spinner"; /spɪnər/) are elements of a complex vector space that can be associated with Euclidean space.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Spinors can be thought of as companion geometric objects to Euclidean space that, like Euclidean vectors, respond when the Euclidean space is subjected to a rotation.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] A spinor transforms linearly when the Euclidean space is subjected to a slight (infinitesimal) rotation, but unlike geometric vectors and tensors, a spinor transforms to its negative when the space rotates through 360° (see picture).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] It takes a rotation of 720° for a spinor to go back to its original state.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Spinors are therefore often described heuristically as "square roots" of (geometric) vectors, and a geometric vector can be constructed quadratically from a spinor.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Spinors were introduced in geometry by Élie Cartan in 1913.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In the 1920s physicists discovered that spinors are essential to describe the intrinsic angular momentum, or "spin", of the electron and other subatomic particles.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Mathematically, spinors are elements of spaces carrying representations of the spin group or of the associated Clifford algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] After choosing a matrix realization of the Clifford algebra, spinors may be represented concretely as column vectors on which the corresponding gamma matrices act.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] A gradual rotation can be visualized as a ribbon in space.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] A solution of the puzzle is a continuous manipulation of the belt, fixing the endpoints, that untwists it.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] This is impossible with the 360° rotation, but possible with the 720° rotation.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] in the rotation group between the 720° rotation and the 0° identity rotation.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] What characterizes spinors and distinguishes them from geometric vectors and other tensors is a subtle difference in how they respond to rotations: briefly, spinors respond to rotations in a *path-dependent* way, while vectors respond without seeing the path through which a rotation was achieved.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Consider applying a rotation to the coordinates of a system.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] No object in the system itself has moved, only the coordinates have, so there will always be a compensating change in those coordinate values when applied to any object of the system.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Geometrical vectors, for example, have components that will undergo *the same* rotation as the coordinates.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] More broadly, any tensor associated with the system (for instance, the stress of some medium) also has coordinate descriptions that adjust to compensate for changes to the coordinate system itself.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Spinors do not appear at this level of the description of a physical system, when one is concerned only with the properties of a single isolated rotation of the coordinates.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Rather, spinors appear when we imagine that instead of a single rotation, the coordinate system is gradually (continuously) rotated between some initial and final configuration.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] For any of the familiar and intuitive ("tensorial") quantities associated with the system, the transformation law does not depend on the precise details of how the coordinates arrived at their final configuration.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Spinors, on the other hand, are constructed in such a way that makes them *sensitive* to how the gradual rotation of the coordinates arrived there: They exhibit path-dependence.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] It turns out that, for any final configuration of the coordinates, there are actually two ("topologically") inequivalent *gradual* (continuous) rotations of the coordinate system that result in this same configuration.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] This ambiguity is called the homotopy class of the gradual rotation.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The belt trick (shown, in which both ends of the rotated object are physically tethered to an external reference) demonstrates two different rotations, one through an angle of 2π and the other through an angle of 4π, having the same final configurations but different classes.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Spinors actually exhibit a sign-reversal that genuinely depends on this homotopy class.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] This distinguishes them from vectors and other tensors, none of which can feel the class.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] To see how this might work in practice, we consider the set $H_{2}$ of $2\times 2$ Hermitian matrices, with complex entries, whose traces are zero.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Any such matrix can be written as $X={\begin{bmatrix}x&z\\{\bar {z}}&-x\end{bmatrix}},$ where x is real, $z=u+iv$ is complex, and ${\bar {z}}=u-iv$ is the complex conjugate of z .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Then $H_{2}$ is a three-dimensional vector space over the real field.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The negative determinant of X is $-\det X=x^{2}+|z|^{2}=x^{2}+u^{2}+v^{2}$ , which is the sum of the squares of the three real coordinates $(x,u,v)$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Thus, $H_{2}$ , equipped with this form, is a real Euclidean three-space (like $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ equipped with its dot product).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In this example, the *spinors* are by definition the complex column vectors on which the special unitary matrices U act.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] These *do* feel the difference between the matrices U and $-U$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The association of the rotation $R_{U}$ to each U is two-to-one, and the kernel is the group $\{\pm I_{2}\}$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] This exhibits the double cover of the rotation group, and $\operatorname {SU} (2)$ as its spin group.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In this setting, the Euclidean space (of "physical vectors") is the real vector space $H_{2}$ , while the space of spinors is the complex two-dimensional vector space of column vectors on which $\operatorname {SU} (2)$ acts.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Thus "vectors" are quadratic in the spinors.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Thus, in the case of three-dimensional rotations, spinors can be defined as follows: A spinor is a complex 2-component column vector $v\in \mathbb {C} ^{2}$ transforming under the natural action of $\operatorname {SU} (2)$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The associated geometric vectors are the traceless Hermitian $2\times 2$ matrices, transforming by conjugation $X\mapsto UXU^{*}$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Thus the spinors are the column vectors themselves, while the ordinary vectors are the objects derived from them that transform under the corresponding rotation action.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Exhibiting spinors as concrete objects in higher dimensions, as in this three-dimensional example, generally requires constructions that depend on the dimension and on the signature of the quadratic form (for example, in Minkowski space).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In general, spinors are described using the Clifford algebra or, equivalently, as representations of the spin group.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] After choosing a matrix realization of the Clifford algebra, the spinors may be represented concretely as column vectors on which the corresponding gamma matrices act.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] A space of spinors is formally defined as an irreducible module of the Clifford algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Over the real or complex numbers, the Clifford algebra is a semisimple algebra, and therefore decomposes as a direct sum of full matrix algebras over a division ring, by the Artin–Wedderburn theorem.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Spinor spaces are the irreducible spaces on which these components act.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Thus a spinor is a "column vector" on which one of these matrix algebras acts.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The space of spinors may also be defined as a spin representation of the orthogonal Lie algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] These spin representations are also characterized as the finite-dimensional projective representations of the special orthogonal group that do not factor through linear representations.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Equivalently, a spinor is an element of a finite-dimensional group representation of the spin group on which the center acts non-trivially.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] There are essentially two frameworks for viewing the notion of a spinor: the *representation theoretic point of view* and the *geometric point of view*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] From a representation theoretic point of view, one knows beforehand that there are some representations of the Lie algebra of the orthogonal group that cannot be formed by the usual tensor constructions.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] These missing representations are then labeled the **spin representations**, and their constituents *spinors*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] These double covers are Lie groups, called the spin groups Spin(*n*) or Spin(*p*, *q*).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] All the properties of spinors, and their applications and derived objects, are manifested first in the spin group.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Representations of the double covers of these groups yield double-valued projective representations of the groups themselves.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In summary, given a representation specified by the data $(V,{\text{Spin}}(p,q),\rho )$ where V is a vector space over $K=\mathbb {R}$ or $\mathbb {C}$ and $\rho$ is a homomorphism $\rho :{\text{Spin}}(p,q)\rightarrow {\text{GL}}(V)$ , a **spinor** is an element of the vector space V .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] From a geometrical point of view, one can explicitly construct the spinors and then examine how they behave under the action of the relevant Lie groups.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] This latter approach has the advantage of providing a concrete and elementary description of what a spinor is.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] However, such a description becomes unwieldy when complicated properties of the spinors, such as Fierz identities, are needed.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The language of Clifford algebras (sometimes called geometric algebras) provides a complete picture of the spin representations of all the spin groups, and the various relationships between those representations, via the classification of Clifford algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] It largely removes the need for *ad hoc* constructions.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In detail, let *V* be a finite-dimensional complex vector space with nondegenerate symmetric bilinear form *g*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The Clifford algebra Cℓ(*V*, *g*) is the algebra generated by *V* subject to the anticommutation relation *xy* + *yx* = 2*g*(*x*, *y*).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] It is an abstract version of the algebra generated by the gamma or Pauli matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] If *n* = 2*k* is even, then Cℓ*n*(ℂ) is isomorphic, noncanonically, to Mat(2*k*, ℂ), so it has a unique irreducible module Δ of dimension 2*k*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] If *n* = 2*k* + 1 is odd, then Cℓ*n*(ℂ) is isomorphic to Mat(2*k*, ℂ) ⊕ Mat(2*k*, ℂ), and therefore has two inequivalent irreducible modules, each of dimension 2*k*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The Lie algebra **so**(*V*, *g*) embeds in the even part of the Clifford algebra, equipped with the commutator bracket, and hence acts on these modules.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] When *n* is odd, the two irreducible Clifford modules restrict to isomorphic irreducible representations of **so**(*V*, *g*); this representation is called the spin representation and is often denoted Δ.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Irreducible representations over the reals in the case when *V* is a real vector space are much more intricate, and the reader is referred to the Clifford algebra article for more details.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Spinors form a vector space, usually over the complex numbers, equipped with a linear group representation of the spin group that does not factor through a representation of the group of rotations (see diagram).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The spin group is the group of rotations keeping track of the homotopy class.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Spinors are needed to encode basic information about the topology of the group of rotations because that group is not simply connected, but the simply connected spin group is its double cover.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] So for every rotation there are two elements of the spin group that represent it.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Geometric vectors and other tensors cannot feel the difference between these two elements, but they produce *opposite* signs when they affect any spinor under the representation.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Thinking of the elements of the spin group as homotopy classes of one-parameter families of rotations, each rotation is represented by two distinct homotopy classes of paths to the identity.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The space of spinors is an auxiliary vector space that can be constructed explicitly in coordinates, but ultimately only exists up to isomorphism in that there is no "natural" construction of them that does not rely on arbitrary choices such as coordinate systems.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] A notion of spinors can be associated, as such an auxiliary mathematical object, with any vector space equipped with a quadratic form such as Euclidean space with its standard dot product, or Minkowski space with its Lorentz metric.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In the latter case, the "rotations" include the Lorentz boosts, but otherwise the theory is substantially similar.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In physics, a **spinor field** is a field whose values lie in a spinor representation.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] On Minkowski space, or more generally on a spacetime manifold that admits a spin structure, one forms a spinor bundle associated to the principal spin bundle and a chosen spin representation; spinor fields are sections of this bundle.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In flat spacetime this bundle may be trivialized, so spinor fields are often written simply as spinor-valued functions on spacetime.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The most common spinor fields in relativistic physics are *Dirac*, *Weyl*, and *Majorana* spinor fields.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] A *Dirac spinor* is a section of the full complex spinor bundle.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In even dimensions, when the spin representation splits into chiral halves, sections of the two summands are called *Weyl spinors*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] A *Majorana spinor* is a spinor satisfying a reality condition, when the relevant spin representation admits one.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Spinor fields enter physics through equations such as the Dirac equation and the Weyl equation, which are first-order differential equations on the spinor bundle.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] These equations describe relativistic fields of spin 1⁄2 and play a central role in quantum field theory and differential geometry.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] For further details, see Dirac spinor, Weyl spinor, Majorana spinor, and spinor bundle.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] One major mathematical application of the construction of spinors is to make possible the explicit construction of linear representations of the Lie algebras of the special orthogonal groups, and consequently spinor representations of the groups themselves.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] At a more profound level, spinors have been found to be at the heart of approaches to the Atiyah–Singer index theorem, and to provide constructions in particular for discrete series representations of semisimple groups.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The spin representations of the special orthogonal Lie algebras are distinguished from the tensor representations given by Weyl's construction by the weights.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Whereas the weights of the tensor representations are integer linear combinations of the roots of the Lie algebra, those of the spin representations are half-integer linear combinations thereof.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Explicit details can be found in the spin representation article.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The spinor can be described, in simple terms, as "vectors of a space the transformations of which are related in a particular way to rotations in physical space".
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Several ways of illustrating everyday analogies have been formulated in terms of the plate trick, tangloids and other examples of orientation entanglement.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The most general mathematical form of spinors was discovered by Élie Cartan in 1913.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The word "spinor" was coined by Paul Ehrenfest in his work on quantum physics.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Spinors were first applied to mathematical physics by Wolfgang Pauli in 1927, when he introduced his spin matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The following year, Paul Dirac discovered the fully relativistic theory of electron spin by showing the connection between spinors and the Lorentz group.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] By the 1930s, Dirac, Piet Hein and others at the Niels Bohr Institute (then known as the Institute for Theoretical Physics of the University of Copenhagen) created toys such as Tangloids to teach and model the calculus of spinors.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Spinor spaces were represented as left ideals of a matrix algebra in 1930, by Gustave Juvett and by Fritz Sauter.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] More specifically, instead of representing spinors as complex-valued 2D column vectors as Pauli had done, they represented them as complex-valued 2 × 2 matrices in which only the elements of the left column are non-zero.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In this manner the spinor space became a minimal left ideal in Mat(2, ℂ).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In 1947 Marcel Riesz constructed spinor spaces as elements of a minimal left ideal of Clifford algebras.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In 1966/1967, David Hestenes replaced spinor spaces by the even subalgebra Cℓ01,3( $\mathbb {R}$ ) of the spacetime algebra Cℓ1,3( $\mathbb {R}$ ).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] As of the 1980s, the theoretical physics group at Birkbeck College around David Bohm and Basil Hiley has been developing algebraic approaches to quantum theory that build on Sauter and Riesz' identification of spinors with minimal left ideals.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Some simple examples of spinors in low dimensions arise from considering the even-graded subalgebras of the Clifford algebra Cℓ*p*, *q*( $\mathbb {R}$ ).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The Clifford algebra Cℓ2,0( $\mathbb {R}$ ) is built up from a basis of one unit scalar, 1, two orthogonal unit vectors, *σ*1 and *σ*2, and one unit pseudoscalar *i* = *σ*1*σ*2.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The even subalgebra Cℓ02,0( $\mathbb {R}$ ), spanned by *even-graded* basis elements of Cℓ2,0( $\mathbb {R}$ ), determines the space of spinors via its representations.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] It is made up of real linear combinations of 1 and *σ*1*σ*2.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] As a real algebra, Cℓ02,0( $\mathbb {R}$ ) is isomorphic to the field of complex numbers $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In this situation, a **spinor** is an ordinary complex number.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] An important feature of this definition is the distinction between ordinary vectors and spinors, manifested in how the even-graded elements act on each of them in different ways.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] On the other hand, in comparison with its action on spinors $\gamma (\phi )=\gamma \phi$ , the action of $\gamma$ on ordinary vectors appears as the *square* of its action on spinors.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Consider, for example, the implication this has for plane rotations.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Rotating a vector through an angle of *θ* corresponds to *γ*2 = exp(*θ σ*1*σ*2), so that the corresponding action on spinors is via *γ* = ± exp(*θ σ*1*σ*2/2).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In general, because of logarithmic branching, it is impossible to choose a sign in a consistent way.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Thus the representation of plane rotations on spinors is two-valued.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In applications of spinors in two dimensions, it is common to exploit the fact that the algebra of even-graded elements (that is just the ring of complex numbers) is identical to the space of spinors.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] So, by abuse of language, the two are often conflated.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] One may then talk about "the action of a spinor on a vector".
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In a general setting, such statements are meaningless.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] But in dimensions 2 and 3 (as applied, for example, to computer graphics) they make sense.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The Clifford algebra Cℓ3,0( $\mathbb {R}$ ) is built up from a basis of one unit scalar, 1, three orthogonal unit vectors, *σ*1, *σ*2 and *σ*3, the three unit bivectors *σ*1*σ*2, *σ*2*σ*3, *σ*3*σ*1 and the pseudoscalar *i* = *σ*1*σ*2*σ*3.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] corresponds to a vector rotation through an angle *θ* about an axis defined by a unit vector *v* = *a*1*σ*1 + *a*2*σ*2 + *a*3*σ*3.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] With the identification of the even-graded elements with the algebra $\mathbb {H}$ of quaternions, as in the case of two dimensions the only representation of the algebra of even-graded elements is on itself.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Thus the (real) spinors in three-dimensions are quaternions, and the action of an even-graded element on a spinor is given by ordinary quaternionic multiplication.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Note that the expression (1) for a vector rotation through an angle θ, *the angle appearing in γ was halved*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Thus the spinor rotation *γ*(*ψ*) = *γψ* (ordinary quaternionic multiplication) will rotate the spinor ψ through an angle one-half the measure of the angle of the corresponding vector rotation.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Once again, the problem of lifting a vector rotation to a spinor rotation is two-valued: the expression (1) with (180° + *θ*/2) in place of *θ*/2 will produce the same vector rotation, but the negative of the spinor rotation.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] A space of spinors can be constructed explicitly with concrete and abstract constructions.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The equivalence of these constructions is a consequence of the uniqueness of the spinor representation of the complex Clifford algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] For a complete example in dimension 3, see spinors in three dimensions.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Given a vector space *V* and a quadratic form *g* an explicit matrix representation of the Clifford algebra Cℓ(*V*, *g*) can be defined as follows.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Then the assignment *e**μ* → *γ**μ* extends uniquely to an algebra homomorphism Cℓ(*V*, *g*) → Mat(2*k*, ℂ) by sending the monomial *e**μ*1 ⋅⋅⋅ *e**μ**k* in the Clifford algebra to the product *γ**μ*1 ⋅⋅⋅ *γ**μ**k* of matrices and extending linearly.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The space $\Delta =\mathbb {C} ^{2^{k}}$ on which the gamma matrices act is now a space of spinors.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] One needs to construct such matrices explicitly, however.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In dimension 3, defining the gamma matrices to be the Pauli sigma matrices gives rise to the familiar two component spinors used in non relativistic quantum mechanics.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Likewise using the 4 × 4 Dirac gamma matrices gives rise to the 4 component Dirac spinors used in 3+1 dimensional relativistic quantum field theory.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In general, in order to define gamma matrices of the required kind, one can use the Weyl–Brauer matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In this construction the representation of the Clifford algebra Cℓ(*V*, *g*), the Lie algebra **so**(*V*, *g*), and the Spin group Spin(*V*, *g*), all depend on the choice of the orthonormal basis and the choice of the gamma matrices.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] This can cause confusion over conventions, but invariants like traces are independent of choices.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In particular, all physically observable quantities must be independent of such choices.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In this construction a spinor can be represented as a vector of 2*k* complex numbers and is denoted with spinor indices (usually *α*, *β*, *γ*).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In the physics literature, such indices are often used to denote spinors even when an abstract spinor construction is used.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] There are at least two different, but essentially equivalent, ways to define spinors abstractly.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] One approach seeks to identify the minimal ideals for the left action of Cℓ(*V*, *g*) on itself.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] These are subspaces of the Clifford algebra of the form Cℓ(*V*, *g*)*ω*, admitting the evident action of Cℓ(*V*, *g*) by left-multiplication: *c* : *xω* → *cxω*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] There are two variations on this theme: one can either find a primitive element *ω* that is a nilpotent element of the Clifford algebra, or one that is an idempotent.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The construction via nilpotent elements is more fundamental in the sense that an idempotent may then be produced from it.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In this way, the spinor representations are identified with certain subspaces of the Clifford algebra itself.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The second approach is to construct a vector space using a distinguished subspace of *V*, and then specify the action of the Clifford algebra *externally* to that vector space.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In either approach, the fundamental notion is that of an isotropic subspace *W*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Each construction depends on an initial freedom in choosing this subspace.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In physical terms, this corresponds to the fact that there is no measurement protocol that can specify a basis of the spin space, even if a preferred basis of *V* is given.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] As above, we let (*V*, *g*) be an *n*-dimensional complex vector space equipped with a nondegenerate bilinear form.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] If *V* is a real vector space, then we replace *V* by its complexification $V\otimes _{\mathbb {R} }\mathbb {C}$ and let *g* denote the induced bilinear form on $V\otimes _{\mathbb {R} }\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Let *W* be a maximal isotropic subspace, i.e. a maximal subspace of *V* such that *g*|*W* = 0.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] If *n* = 2*k* is even, then let *W*′ be an isotropic subspace complementary to *W*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] If *n* = 2*k* + 1 is odd, let *W*′ be a maximal isotropic subspace with *W* ∩ *W*′ = 0, and let *U* be the orthogonal complement of *W* ⊕ *W*′.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In both the even- and odd-dimensional cases *W* and *W*′ have dimension *k*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In the odd-dimensional case, *U* is one-dimensional, spanned by a unit vector *u*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Since *W*′ is isotropic, multiplication of elements of *W*′ inside Cℓ(*V*, *g*) is skew.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Hence vectors in *W*′ anti-commute, and Cℓ(*W*′, *g*|*W*′) = Cℓ(*W*′, 0) is just the exterior algebra Λ∗*W*′.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Consequently, the *k*-fold product of *W*′ with itself, *W*′*k*, is one-dimensional.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] If *n* = 2*k* + 1, then the action of the unit vector *u* on the left ideal Cℓ(*V*, *g*)*ω* decomposes the space into a pair of isomorphic irreducible eigenspaces (both denoted by Δ), corresponding to the respective eigenvalues +1 and −1.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In detail, suppose for instance that *n* is even.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Suppose that *I* is a non-zero left ideal contained in Cℓ(*V*, *g*)*ω*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] We shall show that *I* must be equal to Cℓ(*V*, *g*)*ω* by proving that it contains a nonzero scalar multiple of *ω*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Note that any element of *I* must have the form *αω*, by virtue of our assumption that *I* ⊂ Cℓ(*V*, *g*) *ω*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Note that for *n* even, this computation also shows that $\Delta =\mathrm {C} \ell (W)\omega =\left(\Lambda ^{*}W\right)\omega$ as a vector space.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In the last equality we again used that *W* is isotropic.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In physics terms, this shows that Δ is built up like a Fock space by creating spinors using anti-commuting creation operators in *W* acting on a vacuum *ω*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The computations with the minimal ideal construction suggest that a spinor representation can also be defined directly using the exterior algebra Λ∗ *W* = ⊕*j* Λ*j* *W* of the isotropic subspace *W*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Let Δ = Λ∗ *W* denote the exterior algebra of *W* considered as vector space only.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] This will be the spin representation, and its elements will be referred to as spinors.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The details differ slightly according to whether the dimension of *V* is even or odd.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] When dim(V) is even, *V* = *W* ⊕ *W*′ where *W*′ is the chosen isotropic complement.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] This action is sometimes called the **Clifford product**.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] It may be verified that $c(u)\,c(v)+c(v)\,c(u)=2\,g(u,v)\,,$ and so c respects the Clifford relations and extends to a homomorphism from the Clifford algebra to End(Δ).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] When dim(*V*) is odd, *V* = *W* ⊕ *U* ⊕ *W*′, where *U* is spanned by a unit vector *u* orthogonal to *W*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] If the vector space *V* has extra structure that provides a decomposition of its complexification into two maximal isotropic subspaces, then the definition of spinors (by either method) becomes natural.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The main example is the case that the real vector space *V* is a hermitian vector space (*V*, *g*), i.e., *V* is equipped with a complex structure *J* that is an orthogonal transformation with respect to the inner product *g* on *V*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Then $V\otimes _{\mathbb {R} }\mathbb {C}$ splits in the ±*i* eigenspaces of *J*.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] These eigenspaces are isotropic for the complexification of *g* and can be identified with the complex vector space (*V*, *J*) and its complex conjugate (*V*, −*J*).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Therefore, for a hermitian vector space (*V*, *g*) the vector space $\Lambda _{\mathbb {C} }^{\cdot }{\bar {V}}$ (as well as its complex conjugate $\Lambda _{\mathbb {C} }^{\cdot }V$ ) is a spinor space for the underlying real euclidean vector space.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] With the Clifford action as above but with contraction using the hermitian form, this construction gives a spinor space at every point of an almost Hermitian manifold and is the reason why every almost complex manifold (in particular every symplectic manifold) has a Spinc structure.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Likewise, every complex vector bundle on a manifold carries a Spinc structure.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] A number of Clebsch–Gordan decompositions are possible on the tensor product of one spin representation with another.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] These decompositions express the tensor product in terms of the alternating representations of the orthogonal group.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] The rightmost formulation follows from the transformation properties of the Hodge star operator.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Note that on restriction to the even Clifford algebra, the paired summands Γ*p* ⊕ *σ*Γ*p* are isomorphic, but under the full Clifford algebra they are not.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] There is a natural identification of Δ with its contragredient representation via the conjugation in the Clifford algebra: $(\alpha \omega )^{*}=\omega \left(\alpha ^{*}\right).$ So Δ ⊗ Δ also decomposes in the above manner.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] For the complex representations of the real Clifford algebras, the associated reality structure on the complex Clifford algebra descends to the space of spinors (via the explicit construction in terms of minimal ideals, for instance).
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] In particular, note that the representation Δ of the orthochronous spin group is a unitary representation.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] Using these isomorphisms, one can deduce analogous decompositions for the tensor products of the half-spin representations Δ± ⊗ Δ±.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p01] There are many far-reaching consequences of the Clebsch–Gordan decompositions of the spinor spaces.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p02] One source of confusion is that the words *real*, *complex*, and *quaternionic* are used in two closely related but not identical senses: they may refer to the ground field of a chosen Clifford module, or to the **type** (also called the Schur type) of an irreducible spin representation.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p02] For the spin group, the second notion is the useful one.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p02] Let S be an irreducible complex spin representation of $\operatorname {Spin} (p,q)$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p02] When S is of real type, the fixed-point set of J gives a real form of the representation; this is the algebraic origin of Majorana conditions.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p02] When S is of quaternionic type, the representation carries an invariant quaternionic structure but no invariant real structure on an irreducible complex module.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p02] The reason for the mod-8 pattern is that spinors are naturally modules for the **even Clifford algebra** $\mathrm {C} \ell _{p,q}^{0}$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p02] If S is an irreducible real $\mathrm {C} \ell _{p,q}^{0}$ -module, then by Schur's lemma its commuting algebra $\operatorname {End} _{\mathrm {C} \ell _{p,q}^{0}}(S)$ is a finite-dimensional real division algebra.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p02] By the Frobenius theorem, it is therefore isomorphic to exactly one of $\mathbb {R} ,\qquad \mathbb {C} ,\qquad \mathbb {H} .$ These three possibilities are precisely the real, complex, and quaternionic types.
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p02] Using the standard identification of even Clifford algebras with Clifford algebras in one lower dimension, together with Bott periodicity, one finds that the type depends only on $p-q{\pmod {8}}$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p02] A common source of apparent disagreement between tables in the literature is that some authors classify irreducible modules for the full real Clifford algebra $\mathrm {C} \ell _{p,q}$ , while others classify spin representations of $\operatorname {Spin} (p,q)$ .
[src:clifford-algebra/spinor-p02] Since the spin group sits in the even Clifford algebra, these two tables differ by a shift of one step in the mod-8 pattern.
